  :composes-with     "memory/project_cpt_is_over_nouns.md (CPT is over nouns doctrine); memory/project_four_axis_graph_consolidation.md (four-axis graph consolidation); memory/project_signifier_signified_and_dialogue.md (signifier / signified / dialogue per concept); memory/project_graph_derivation_principle.md (graph derivation principle); engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat (node schema each surviving word maps into); engineering/LACUNA-ENG-CPT-SHAPES-RESEARCH-2026-07-20.md (why CPT presentation shapes matter); SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-type.slat (downstream authoring runbook consuming these seed lists)"

  :section-0-purpose
  """
  This chapter documents the CORPUS → GRAPH DERIVATION PROCEDURE
  Alfred approved on 2026-07-20. It is the deterministic path from
  raw authored corpus (books + word-books + reference) to axis-
  classified seed lists that populate the four Jung-axis graphs
  (Sensation / Intuition / Thinking / Feeling).

  The procedure is a pipeline of eight mechanical steps, all
  reproducible from files on disk. Every step's inputs are files;
  every step's outputs are TSV or SLAT. No LLM invents content.
  No scraping. No external corpora. Rerun the same procedure over
  the same corpus and you get the same output; rerun over an
  updated corpus and the differences are semantically meaningful
  (new nouns, shifted frequencies) rather than stochastic noise.

  Read this chapter end-to-end before running any step. Then work
  through the sections in order. Each step names its inputs, its
  outputs, its script, and its verification check.

  Who this is for:
    · Anyone rerunning graph derivation on Motoi as the corpus
      grows past its current 856-file / 25k-distinct-word state.
    · The Sakura team, applying the same procedure to Sakura's
      corpus to derive Sakura's own Pareto-cut axis seed lists.
    · Any future agent tasked with 'give me the graph seed list'
      — the answer is 'run this chapter'; do not improvise a
      lexicon-based classifier or a word-frequency guess.

  The pedagogical point (memory/project_graph_derivation_principle):
  a graph node earns its place by RECURRENCE in the corpus. A word
  that appears once is not part of the language; a word that appears
  hundreds of times is a signifier the model must reify. The Pareto
  cut is the principled place to draw the line between 'part of
  the language' and 'incidental noise'. Downstream, each surviving
  word becomes a graph node per JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA, and
  the graph feeds CPT extraction per chapter 4.
  """

  :section-1-preconditions
  """
  Before running the pipeline:

  [ ] Books present and enumerable:
      ls /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      Expect: current run had 728 chapter files across 30+ books.

  [ ] Word-books present and enumerable:
      ls /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      Expect: current run had 50 word-book chapter files.

  [ ] Reference present:
      ls /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/Scheme/reference/*.slat
      Expect: current run had 78 reference files.

  [ ] Doctrine composes-with (READ FIRST):
      · memory/project_cpt_is_over_nouns.md
        CPT is over NOUNS not verbs — this is why we derive noun
        seed lists here, not verb lists. Verbs come from the
        reference; nouns must be derived from corpus recurrence.
      · memory/project_four_axis_graph_consolidation.md
        The 10 canonical graph types consolidate into 4 Jung axes:
        Sensation (person/object/place/institution),
        Intuition (concept/event/cultural-work/art-movement),
        Thinking (do-and-dont), Feeling (register).
      · memory/project_signifier_signified_and_dialogue.md
        Each graph node carries a signifier (name), a signified
        (concept content), and a per-node dialogue field.
      · memory/project_graph_derivation_principle.md
        Recurrence earns a place in the graph. Pareto is the cut.
      · engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat
        Per-axis node field schema each surviving word maps into.
      · engineering/LACUNA-ENG-CPT-SHAPES-RESEARCH-2026-07-20.md
        Downstream — why each graph node needs multi-shape CPT
        presentation to become extractable knowledge.

  [ ] Scripts drafted and versioned:
      ls /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/scripts/derive-graph-seeds/
      Expect these files (author to skeletons below if missing):
        01-extract-tokens.py     — Step 1 extractor
        02-distribution.py       — Step 2 Zipf / percentile analysis
        03-pareto-cut.py         — Step 3 canonical cut
        04-drop-workhorses.py    — Step 4 top-100 drop
        05-axis-classify.py      — Step 5 evidence-driven classifier
        06-emit-seed-tsv.py      — Step 6 per-axis seed TSV writer
        stopwords-scheme.txt     — the Scheme/language stopword list
        stopwords-english.txt    — the English stopword list
        workhorses.txt           — the top-100 workhorse-word drop list

  [ ] Output directories prepared:
      mkdir -p /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/derived/graph-seeds/{raw,dist,cut,axis-seeds}
        raw/       — Step 1 output (frequency TSV)
        dist/      — Step 2 output (distribution stats)
        cut/       — Step 3+4 output (after Pareto + workhorse drop)
        axis-seeds/— Step 6 output (per-axis seed lists)

  [ ] Runlog file opened:
      /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/derived/graph-seeds/RUN-<date>.log
      Every step appends its command line + stdout summary here.
      Reproducibility depends on the log.

  Skip none. Pipeline failures caught early are cheap; failures
  caught after axis-classification wastes agent-hours.
  """

  :section-2-extraction
  """
  STEP 1 — EXTRACTION (mechanical, deterministic).

  GOAL: scan every corpus file, tokenize to lowercase content-words,
  drop stopwords, produce a frequency map (word → count) as TSV.

  INPUTS:
    /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
    /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
    /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/Scheme/reference/*.slat

  OUTPUT:
    /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme/derived/graph-seeds/raw/frequency.tsv
    format: <count>\\t<word>  (sorted by count descending, then word ascending)

  TOKENIZER:
    Regex: [a-z]+
    Rules applied in order:
      (a) lowercase the entire file text
      (b) split on the regex above (numbers and punctuation are
          natural delimiters, NOT preserved as tokens)
      (c) drop tokens with length < 3
      (d) drop pure-numeric tokens (redundant after regex but kept
          for defense-in-depth against future tokenizer changes)
      (e) drop tokens in the Scheme/language stopword list
      (f) drop tokens in the common-English stopword list

  SCHEME / LANGUAGE STOPWORD LIST (full — commit to
  scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-scheme.txt verbatim):

    define lambda let if cond else car cdr cons list pair null
    true false quote quasiquote unquote and or not when unless
    begin do map for-each apply eval error set letrec delay
    force dynamic-wind call-with-current-continuation call-cc
    values receive module import export dialect applies name
    canonical provenance source book chapter code verb kind
    signature contract examples note ref id level novice
    intermediate expert

  ENGLISH STOPWORD LIST (full — commit to
  scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-english.txt verbatim):

    the a an and or but if of to in on at for from by with as
    is are was were be been being have has had do does did will
    would should could may might must can shall this that these
    those it its there here their they them we us you your our
    my me mine yours ours his her hers he she who whom whose
    which what where when why how all any some no not none only
    just also very much many few most more less than then so
    such because while about into over under above below between
    through during before after around across along without within
    up down out off again still yet already always never sometimes
    often once twice each every other another same different way
    ways thing things something anything nothing everything one
    two three four five six seven eight nine ten first second
    third last next new old good bad big small long short high
    low make made makes making take took taken taking get got
    gets getting go went gone going come came comes coming say
    said says saying see saw seen seeing know knew known knowing
    think thought thinking want wanted wants wanting use used
    uses using find found finds finding tell told tells telling
    ask asked asks asking work worked works working seem seemed
    seems seeming feel felt feels feeling try tried tries trying
    leave left leaves leaving call called calls calling put puts
    putting mean means meant meaning let lets letting show showed
    shown shows showing keep kept keeps keeping let just also
    quite really actually probably perhaps maybe possibly certainly
    definitely usually mostly generally typically simply merely
    even though although however therefore thus hence furthermore
    moreover meanwhile otherwise instead rather besides likewise
    similarly conversely nevertheless nonetheless

    (Full list ~250 tokens. Regenerate deterministically by running
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/generate-english-stopwords.py once;
    hash the result and pin to the runlog. If English stopword
    reference-list evolves upstream, do NOT let it drift silently
    — always version-pin.)

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/01-extract-tokens.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    import re
    import sys
    from collections import Counter
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')

    GLOBS = [
        'scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
        'word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
        'Scheme/reference/*.slat',
    ]

    def load_stopwords(path):
        return set(w.strip() for w in Path(path).read_text().split()
                   if w.strip())

    STOP_SCHEME = load_stopwords(
        'scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-scheme.txt')
    STOP_ENGLISH = load_stopwords(
        'scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-english.txt')
    STOP = STOP_SCHEME | STOP_ENGLISH

    TOK = re.compile(r'[a-z]+')

    def tokenize(text):
        for tok in TOK.findall(text.lower()):
            if len(tok) < 3:
                continue
            if tok.isdigit():          # defense-in-depth
                continue
            if tok in STOP:
                continue
            yield tok

    def main():
        counts = Counter()
        files_scanned = 0
        for glob in GLOBS:
            for path in ROOT.glob(glob):
                text = path.read_text(errors='replace')
                counts.update(tokenize(text))
                files_scanned += 1

        out_path = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/raw/frequency.tsv'
        out_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
        with out_path.open('w') as f:
            for word, cnt in sorted(counts.items(),
                                    key=lambda kv: (-kv[1], kv[0])):
                f.write(f'{cnt}\\t{word}\\n')

        print(f'files scanned:        {files_scanned}')
        print(f'distinct tokens:      {len(counts)}')
        print(f'total token count:    {sum(counts.values())}')
        print(f'wrote:                {out_path}')

    if __name__ == '__main__':
        main()

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/01-extract-tokens.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] Files scanned matches expectation for corpus size (current
        canonical baseline: 856).
    [ ] Distinct token count in the low tens-of-thousands (current:
        25,272).
    [ ] Total tokens in the low millions (current: 1,542,121).
    [ ] Top-10 rows of frequency.tsv are Scheme-and-Motoi glue words
        (scheme, motoi, entity, world, etc.) — if not, tokenizer is
        broken.
    [ ] Bottom-10 rows are rare content-words each appearing once —
        the long tail confirms the tokenizer isn't silently
        combining or dropping.

  DEFECT HANDLING:
    Any file that fails to read logs a warning to the runlog but
    does NOT halt the pipeline. Corrupted or non-UTF8 files are
    rare; report count in log summary.
  """

  :section-3-distribution-analysis
  """
  STEP 2 — DISTRIBUTION ANALYSIS.

  GOAL: characterize the frequency distribution. Confirm the corpus
  has the expected Zipfian shape (technical corpora are flatter than
  natural English); compute rank-frequency, log-log slope, and
  cumulative-mass percentiles so Step 3 can find the Pareto cut.

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/raw/frequency.tsv

  OUTPUTS:
    derived/graph-seeds/dist/rank-freq.tsv
      columns: rank \\t freq \\t word \\t cumulative_freq \\t cumulative_pct
    derived/graph-seeds/dist/percentiles.tsv
      columns: percentile \\t rank_at_percentile \\t freq_at_percentile
    derived/graph-seeds/dist/zipf-fit.txt
      log-log slope alpha, R^2, and a one-line summary

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/02-distribution.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    import math
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
    IN   = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/raw/frequency.tsv'
    OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/dist'
    OUT.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    rows = []
    with IN.open() as f:
        for line in f:
            cnt, word = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
            rows.append((int(cnt), word))
    # rows already sorted by count desc from Step 1

    total = sum(cnt for cnt, _ in rows)
    running = 0

    with (OUT/'rank-freq.tsv').open('w') as out:
        for rank, (cnt, word) in enumerate(rows, start=1):
            running += cnt
            out.write(f'{rank}\\t{cnt}\\t{word}\\t{running}\\t'
                      f'{running/total:.6f}\\n')

    # Percentiles every 5%
    targets = [i/100 for i in range(5, 105, 5)]
    running = 0
    ti = 0
    hits = []
    for rank, (cnt, word) in enumerate(rows, start=1):
        running += cnt
        while ti < len(targets) and running/total >= targets[ti]:
            hits.append((targets[ti], rank, cnt))
            ti += 1
    with (OUT/'percentiles.tsv').open('w') as out:
        out.write('percentile\\trank_at_percentile\\tfreq_at_percentile\\n')
        for pct, rank, cnt in hits:
            out.write(f'{pct:.2f}\\t{rank}\\t{cnt}\\n')

    # Zipf fit: log(freq) = -alpha * log(rank) + c, linear regression
    # in log-log space using ranks 1..min(len(rows), 5000).
    xs, ys = [], []
    for rank, (cnt, _) in enumerate(rows, start=1):
        if rank > 5000: break
        if cnt <= 0: continue
        xs.append(math.log(rank))
        ys.append(math.log(cnt))
    n = len(xs)
    mx = sum(xs)/n; my = sum(ys)/n
    num = sum((x-mx)*(y-my) for x,y in zip(xs,ys))
    den = sum((x-mx)**2 for x in xs)
    slope = num/den
    alpha = -slope
    # R^2
    yhat = [slope*(x-mx) + my for x in xs]
    ss_res = sum((y-yh)**2 for y,yh in zip(ys, yhat))
    ss_tot = sum((y-my)**2 for y in ys)
    r2 = 1 - ss_res/ss_tot

    with (OUT/'zipf-fit.txt').open('w') as out:
        out.write(f'alpha (Zipf exponent): {alpha:.4f}\\n')
        out.write(f'R^2:                   {r2:.4f}\\n')
        out.write(f'ranks used:            1..{min(5000, len(rows))}\\n')
        out.write(f'interpretation:        ')
        if alpha < 0.85:
            out.write('flatter than natural English (curated technical corpus, expected)\\n')
        elif alpha < 1.15:
            out.write('near natural-English Zipf; corpus is well-mixed\\n')
        else:
            out.write('steeper than natural English; heavy head, thin tail — inspect\\n')

    print('distribution analysis done; see', OUT)

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/02-distribution.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  CANONICAL SHAPE (baseline, 2026-07-20 Motoi run):
    Zipf alpha ≈ 0.63 (flatter than English's ~1.0). This is
    EXPECTED for a curated technical corpus — book prose repeats
    domain vocabulary far more than natural English does, so the
    head is fatter (fewer huge outliers) and the tail is longer
    (more distinct rare terms per unit corpus size).

    If alpha comes in >1.15 on a rerun: some author has dumped a
    corpus of repetitive glue (system prompts, boilerplate, or
    scraping contamination). Investigate before proceeding.

    If alpha comes in <0.4: corpus is likely dominated by unique
    per-chapter jargon with little cross-reference. Signals the
    graph derivation will yield high axis coverage but weak
    signifier density; consider prose-book authoring lane to lift
    cross-chapter recurrence.

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] rank-freq.tsv row count = frequency.tsv row count.
    [ ] percentiles.tsv has 20 rows (5% .. 100%).
    [ ] zipf-fit.txt alpha in [0.4, 1.2] range for a healthy
        curated technical corpus.
    [ ] Cumulative % monotonically increasing.
  """

  :section-4-pareto-cut
  """
  STEP 3 — CUT AT PARETO (80% CUMULATIVE MASS) — FIRST-ORDER FILTER.

  ROLE OF THIS STEP (per Alfred 2026-07-21):
    Pareto is a first-order filter that separates 'part of the
    language' from 'incidental noise'. It bounds the working pool
    Step 6b enriches. It IS NOT the Tier 1 selection rule anymore
    — Tier 1 is now TF-IDF top-300 per axis with doc-freq ≥ 5
    (see § 9). Pareto is retained because (a) it is the
    principled, reproducible entry filter, and (b) it keeps
    Step 6b's O(|V|²) distributional-neighbors pass tractable.

  GOAL: draw the principled line between 'part of the language' and
  'incidental noise'. The Pareto (80/20) cut says: the words whose
  combined occurrences make up 80% of all token instances are the
  words the model MUST reify. The remaining 20% mass is spread
  across a long tail of rarely-recurring terms that do not (yet)
  earn a graph node.

  ALFRED 2026-07-20: 'why is 89% better than Pareto?' Answer: it
  isn't. Pareto is the principled cut. Guessed thresholds (89%,
  freq≥50, 'the top N', etc.) are not principled and will drift
  between rerurns and between operators. Pareto is data-driven
  and reproducible. Fewer words each with higher recurrence
  guarantees the signifier density CPT needs.

  MATH:
    Let f_i = frequency of the i-th word in rank order (descending).
    Let T   = sum(f_i for all i) = total token count.
    Let C_k = sum(f_i for i in 1..k) = cumulative token count.
    The Pareto threshold rank k* is:
        k* = min { k : C_k / T >= 0.80 }
    The Pareto frequency threshold is:
        f_thresh = f_{k*}
    The retained vocabulary is:
        V_pareto = { word_i : f_i >= f_thresh }

    Notes:
      · Because ranks with equal frequency are grouped, |V_pareto|
        can slightly exceed k*. That's fine — the CUT is defined by
        frequency, not by rank. Rank is the mechanism.
      · Never round the 0.80. Do not use 0.79 or 0.81 as
        'close enough'. Exactly 0.80 is the doctrine.

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/dist/rank-freq.tsv

  OUTPUTS:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto.tsv
      All rows from rank-freq.tsv where freq >= f_thresh.
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto-summary.txt
      k*, f_thresh, |V_pareto|, total_mass_retained, one-line
      commentary.

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/03-pareto-cut.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
    IN   = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/dist/rank-freq.tsv'
    OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut'
    OUT.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    rows = []
    with IN.open() as f:
        for line in f:
            rank, cnt, word, cum, cum_pct = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
            rows.append((int(rank), int(cnt), word, int(cum),
                         float(cum_pct)))

    # find k* = first rank where cum_pct >= 0.80
    kstar = None
    for r in rows:
        if r[4] >= 0.80:
            kstar = r; break
    if kstar is None:
        raise SystemExit('corpus too small for Pareto cut')
    _, f_thresh, _, _, _ = kstar

    keep = [r for r in rows if r[1] >= f_thresh]
    total_retained = sum(r[1] for r in keep)
    T = sum(r[1] for r in rows)

    with (OUT/'pareto.tsv').open('w') as out:
        for r in keep:
            out.write('\\t'.join(str(x) for x in r) + '\\n')

    with (OUT/'pareto-summary.txt').open('w') as out:
        out.write(f'k* (rank at 80% mass):     {kstar[0]}\\n')
        out.write(f'f_thresh (freq at cut):    {f_thresh}\\n')
        out.write(f'|V_pareto|:                {len(keep)}\\n')
        out.write(f'total_mass_retained:       {total_retained/T:.4f}\\n')
        out.write(f'canonical rule:            keep word if freq >= f_thresh\\n')

    print(f'Pareto cut: k*={kstar[0]} f_thresh={f_thresh} '
          f'|V|={len(keep)}')

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/03-pareto-cut.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  CANONICAL BASELINE (2026-07-20 Motoi run):
    k*         ≈ 2,332
    f_thresh   = 120  (i.e., keep every word appearing ≥120 times)
    |V_pareto| ≈ 2,332  (equal-freq boundaries can shift ±few)

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] pareto-summary.txt exists and total_mass_retained ≥ 0.80.
    [ ] |V_pareto| in low thousands (for corpora of order 10^6
        tokens).
    [ ] The last row in pareto.tsv has freq = f_thresh.
    [ ] wc -l pareto.tsv matches |V_pareto|.
  """

  :section-5-drop-workhorses
  """
  STEP 4 — DROP THE TOP-100 WORKHORSE WORDS.

  GOAL: the top-100 words by frequency are Scheme keywords, glue
  words ('scheme', 'entity', 'world', 'motoi', 'math', 'row',
  'shape', 'display', 'meta', etc.) and universal book scaffolding
  ('chapter', 'section', 'part'). These are already known to the
  base model — a Scheme keyword doesn't need a graph node to teach
  the model what 'define' means. Adding them to the graph teaches
  nothing new and dilutes axis-classification.

  RULE: after Pareto cut, remove the top-100 words by frequency
  from the retained pool. Fixed number, not a percentile — 100 is
  the observed elbow between 'universal glue' and 'domain-content
  noun' on the Motoi corpus. If you find yourself tempted to bump
  it to 150 or 200 on a rerun, that's a signal to author more
  domain content, not to widen the drop.

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto.tsv

  OUTPUTS:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/workhorses.tsv
      The 100 words dropped, with counts (for audit).
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv
      Pareto cut minus the top-100 workhorses.

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/04-drop-workhorses.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
    IN   = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto.tsv'
    OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut'

    rows = []
    with IN.open() as f:
        for line in f:
            parts = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
            rows.append(parts)  # rank, cnt, word, cum, cum_pct

    # Top 100 by frequency (rows are already sorted by cnt desc)
    top100 = rows[:100]
    remainder = rows[100:]

    with (OUT/'workhorses.tsv').open('w') as out:
        for r in top100:
            out.write('\\t'.join(r) + '\\n')

    with (OUT/'pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv').open('w') as out:
        for r in remainder:
            out.write('\\t'.join(r) + '\\n')

    print(f'dropped {len(top100)} workhorse words')
    print(f'remaining pool: {len(remainder)} words')

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/04-drop-workhorses.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  CANONICAL BASELINE (2026-07-20 Motoi run):
    workhorses dropped: 100
    remaining pool:     ~2,232 words

  ALSO COMMIT the workhorse list to
  scripts/derive-graph-seeds/workhorses.txt after each canonical
  run — the file is the diff-record between runs. If a workhorse
  falls out of top-100 in a future rerun, that's a semantically
  meaningful signal about corpus shape drift.

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] workhorses.tsv has exactly 100 rows.
    [ ] pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv row count = |V_pareto| - 100.
    [ ] Manual inspection: workhorses.tsv should look like Scheme
        keywords + book-scaffolding words. If it looks like
        domain-content nouns, tokenizer or stopword list is wrong.
  """

  :section-6-axis-classification
  """
  STEP 5 — EVIDENCE-DRIVEN AXIS CLASSIFICATION.

  GOAL: for each surviving word, assign it to one of the four Jung
  axes, or to the OTHER pool (verbs, adjectives, adverbs — not axis
  material). Classification is EVIDENCE-DRIVEN: the classifier reads
  a corpus context excerpt for each word and decides based on how
  the word is actually used, not on the word's dictionary sense in
  isolation.

  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  ALFRED 2026-07-20 CANONICAL RULE — WHICH WORD GOES IN WHICH GRAPH.
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  This is THE rule. Every future operator (human or agent) rerunning
  Step 5 must follow it verbatim. Deviations are not creative
  improvements; they are classifier drift and produce silently-worse
  graphs. If in doubt, follow the rule to the letter and record the
  ambiguity in :notes for later human review.

  Six steps, executed in this order for every word in
  pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv:

  STEP A — EVIDENCE SAMPLING (deterministic, pre-classification).
    Pull the word's ±5-word context excerpts directly from the
    corpus files that produced the token. For Motoi Mk 1 that is
    the evidence-bundle JSONL (Part A of the script skeleton
    below). Minimum 3 excerpts; target 5. Fewer than 3 excerpts =
    the word did not truly recur; halt and inspect the tokenizer.
    NEVER classify from lexicon or dictionary alone — the corpus
    evidence IS the source of truth.

  STEP B — AXIS FIT TESTS (applied IN ORDER, first match wins
  UNLESS Step D priority tie-break overrides).
    (b.1) Sensation fit — concrete-world referent you can point at.
          Object, animal, plant, place, material, weather, food,
          body-part, people-as-role, sound, color. Test: 'Could a
          child point to this in the physical world?' If yes,
          candidate = Sensation.

    (b.2) Intuition fit — abstract category / pattern / concept.
          Algorithm, math concept, CS concept, data structure,
          relation, art movement, cultural work, event. Test:
          'Is this a NAME for a pattern, category, or abstract
          type rather than a thing?' If yes, candidate = Intuition.

    (b.3) Thinking fit — judgment principle / rule / correctness
          or safety concept. Fairness, correctness, boundary,
          invariant, standard, contract, defect, safety. Test:
          'Does using this word invoke a judgment about right/
          wrong, safe/unsafe, correct/incorrect?' If yes,
          candidate = Thinking.

    (b.4) Feeling fit — tonal / register / valuation quality.
          Calm, urgency, warmth, silence, playfulness, restraint,
          grief, delight, wonder, humor. Test: 'Does the word
          NAME a tone or emotional register rather than a thing,
          concept, or judgment?' If yes, candidate = Feeling.

  STEP C — POLYSEMY RESOLUTION.
    If two axis-fit tests fire on the same word ('table' fires
    Sensation for furniture AND Intuition for hash-table), the
    corpus evidence decides. Count how many excerpts support each
    sense. Dominant use wins. If the dominant-use margin is <60%
    (i.e., 3/5 vs 2/5), mark with :notes AMBIGUOUS and add the
    row to polysemy.tsv for later split-into-two-nodes review.

  STEP D — PRIORITY TIE-BREAK (only when evidence is genuinely
  split and Step C cannot resolve).
    Priority order, high to low:
      Thinking > Intuition > Sensation > Feeling
    Rationale:
      · Judgment before abstract — a rule USES abstract concepts
        but is not merely one of them; the judgment character is
        MORE INFORMATIVE for graph placement.
      · Abstract before concrete — an abstract concept USES
        concrete objects as examples but is not one of them.
      · Concrete before tone — concrete referent is more
        specific than tonal quality when both apply.
    Tie-break is a LAST RESORT. Use only after (b) and (c) have
    genuinely deadlocked. Log every use in :notes ('tie-break: T
    over I because ...').

  STEP E — OTHER POOL (Tier 2 stub only).
    Verbs, adverbs, adjectives without a nominalized noun-role in
    the corpus go into the OTHER pool. They receive Tier 2 stub
    treatment (see section 9). They do NOT get an axis. They DO
    get a canonical entry so the graph knows they exist and
    where they appear.
    OTHER-pool nominalization rule: if evidence shows a verb
    or adjective used as a Sensation object ('the reflection
    on the water', 'the bright of the sun'), reclassify to
    Sensation. Reclamation rate observed on Motoi Mk 1: ~5-10%
    of the OTHER pool.

  STEP F — CROSS-AXIS BRIDGE MARKING.
    After axis assignment, note words that co-occur strongly
    (high PPMI, per Step 6b) with words on OTHER axes. These
    get a :cross-axis-bridge-score flag on their node. The word
    is STILL assigned to its dominant axis; the bridge score is
    additional metadata for graph integration. High-bridge
    words are the connective tissue that keeps the four-axis
    graph from decomposing into four isolated islands.

  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  END OF CANONICAL RULE.
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  AXES (per memory/project_four_axis_graph_consolidation):
    · Sensation — concrete-world nouns
        person, object, place, institution
        Examples: 'hero', 'floor', 'planet', 'school', 'kitchen'
    · Intuition — abstract-category / concept nouns
        concept, event, cultural-work, art-movement
        Examples: 'pattern', 'algorithm', 'symmetry', 'jazz',
        'romanticism', 'election'
    · Thinking — judgment-principle nouns
        do-and-dont
        Examples: 'invariant', 'contract', 'principle', 'law',
        'convention', 'defect', 'safety'
    · Feeling — tonal / register nouns
        register
        Examples: 'kindness', 'gentleness', 'humor', 'grief',
        'joy', 'consolation', 'wonder'
    · OTHER — not axis material
        verbs (nominalized borderline cases reclassify),
        adjectives (borderline: 'freshness' Feeling; 'freshness'
        as chemistry Sensation),
        adverbs (essentially never axis material).

  CORE RULE: CONTEXT BEATS LEXICON.
    'table' used as hash-table → Intuition (concept).
    'table' used as world-object at a kitchen scene → Sensation.
    The evidence excerpt (5-10 lines of surrounding corpus text)
    decides. Where the word appears multiple times with divergent
    senses, add a :notes field noting the polysemy and classify by
    dominant sense — with a follow-up TODO to split into disambig
    entries at graph-population time.

  MOTOI IS NOT KID-ONLY (Alfred 2026-07-20 correction).
    Do NOT filter for kid-vocabulary only. Motoi is a language for
    people of all ages — adult-relevant nouns stay. Sensation should
    include 'kitchen' AND 'election'; Feeling should include
    'delight' AND 'grief'. If the classifier is silently kid-only,
    the graph will underweight adult-register content and the model
    will fail on adult-usage prompts.

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv
    Plus the raw corpus (re-scanned for evidence excerpt lookup):
      scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      Scheme/reference/*.slat

  OUTPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/classified.tsv
      columns: axis \\t word \\t freq \\t evidence_source \\t evidence_snippet \\t notes
      where axis ∈ {sensation, intuition, thinking, feeling, other}

  CLASSIFICATION METHOD:
    Two-pass:
      Pass 1 (lexicon pre-classify): for each word, apply a
        conservative lexicon rule to produce a first-cut axis.
        This is a SEED, not a decision — every word STILL goes
        through Pass 2.
      Pass 2 (evidence-driven confirm-or-reclassify): read the
        first N occurrences of the word in the corpus. Look at
        context. Confirm the Pass 1 label or override it.

    For Motoi Mk 1 (2026-07-20) Pass 2 was performed by a
    Claude-sub-agent given the evidence excerpt AND the axis
    definitions above AND the polysemy handling rule AND the
    'Motoi is not kid-only' correction — the sub-agent proposed
    an axis and a :notes field. Human review (Alfred) can spot-
    check but is not the bottleneck. If the sub-agent is uncertain,
    it MUST emit :notes 'AMBIGUOUS' and let the reviewer decide.

    LLM ROLE (important, per no-contaminants doctrine):
      The LLM classifies existing corpus tokens into axes. It does
      NOT invent tokens. It does NOT add words that aren't in
      pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv. It does NOT change frequencies.
      Its output is one label per input row. The classification is
      an act of reading, not authoring. Provenance for classified
      rows is 'derived: pass-2 evidence classification of
      pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv'.

  RECLASSIFY OTHER POOL FOR NOMINALIZATION:
    A word initially tagged OTHER (verb / adjective) may deserve
    an axis. If 'reflect' is used as a Sensation object ('the
    reflection on the water'), it's Sensation. If 'bright' is
    used nominalized ('the bright of the sun'), it's Sensation.
    Pass 3 sweeps the OTHER pool with the same evidence-driven
    method to reclaim axis-fit nominalizations. Do not lose the
    LARGE OTHER pool though — most of it (verbs, adjectives used
    predicatively) legitimately isn't axis material. Reclamation
    rate on Motoi Mk 1 was ~5-10% of the OTHER pool.

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/05-axis-classify.py):

    Two-part script. Part A produces evidence bundles for each
    word (offline, deterministic). Part B is the LLM classifier
    invocation, driven from a queue.

    Part A — evidence bundle generation (deterministic):

      #!/usr/bin/env python3
      import json, re
      from pathlib import Path

      ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
      POOL = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut/pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv'
      OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut/evidence-bundles.jsonl'

      words = []
      with POOL.open() as f:
          for line in f:
              parts = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
              _, cnt, w, _, _ = parts
              words.append((w, int(cnt)))
      word_set = set(w for w, _ in words)

      GLOBS = [
          'scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
          'word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
          'Scheme/reference/*.slat',
      ]

      # Collect up to 5 excerpts per word
      excerpts = {w: [] for w in word_set}
      for glob in GLOBS:
          for path in ROOT.glob(glob):
              lines = path.read_text(errors='replace').split('\\n')
              lo = path.relative_to(ROOT)
              for i, line in enumerate(lines):
                  toks = set(re.findall(r'[a-z]+', line.lower()))
                  for w in toks & word_set:
                      if len(excerpts[w]) < 5:
                          start = max(0, i-2); end = min(len(lines), i+3)
                          excerpts[w].append({
                              'source': str(lo),
                              'line':   i+1,
                              'text':   '\\n'.join(lines[start:end])
                          })

      with OUT.open('w') as f:
          for w, cnt in words:
              f.write(json.dumps({
                  'word':     w,
                  'freq':     cnt,
                  'excerpts': excerpts[w]
              }) + '\\n')

    Part B — classification (per evidence bundle):

      Feed each bundle to the classifier (LLM sub-agent) with a
      system prompt that includes:
        · the four axis definitions above verbatim
        · the polysemy handling rule
        · the 'Motoi is not kid-only' correction
        · the reclassify-OTHER-nominalization rule
        · the required output schema:
            {'word': ..., 'axis': ..., 'notes': ...}
      Read one bundle at a time. Emit one line per word to
      classified.tsv.

      For determinism: use temperature=0 on the classifier LLM.
      Same evidence bundle → same axis label. If the classifier
      is non-deterministic, pipeline reproducibility fails.

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/05-axis-classify.py --pass=A \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/05-axis-classify.py --pass=B \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  CANONICAL BASELINE (2026-07-20 Motoi run, PRIOR lexicon-based
  Pass 1 at freq≥5, before Pareto cut, illustrative only):
    Sensation:  859
    Intuition:  1,698
    Thinking:   405
    Feeling:    223
    OTHER:      8,550
    (Pass 2 evidence-driven counts pending at time of writing;
    absolute numbers WILL DIFFER on rerun as corpus grows and as
    the Pareto cut narrows the pool — do not memorize.)

  POLYSEMY REGISTRY:
    Words that get classified with :notes 'AMBIGUOUS' or with
    :notes noting a split-sense go into a follow-up file:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/polysemy.tsv
    Reviewed at graph-population time — some will split into two
    graph nodes (e.g., 'table' → 'table [furniture]' Sensation
    + 'table [datastructure]' Intuition). Do not silently pick
    one sense and lose the other.

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] classified.tsv row count = pareto-minus-workhorses.tsv row
        count. Every input word gets a label; nothing dropped
        silently.
    [ ] Every :axis value ∈ {sensation, intuition, thinking,
        feeling, other}. No typos, no other labels.
    [ ] Spot-check 50 random rows manually. Look for obvious
        misclassifications — a Sensation word tagged Feeling is a
        red flag for classifier drift.
    [ ] Axis totals within order-of-magnitude expectation. If
        Feeling collapses to <20 or Thinking spikes to >1000,
        classifier is broken.
  """

  :section-6b-associative-enrichment
  """
  STEP 6b — ASSOCIATIVE ENRICHMENT (TIER 1 ONLY).

  PURPOSE: derived-from-corpus semantic enrichment per graph node.
  Embodies the distributional hypothesis (Firth 1957: 'you shall
  know a word by the company it keeps'). Deterministic, scriptable,
  repeatable, provenance-stampable. Applies ONLY to Tier 1 nodes
  (the ~960 per-axis Pareto words that earned full graph-node
  treatment).

  Without this step, graph nodes are isolated definitions. With
  it, they form a real semantic network — every node knows its
  neighborhood, its semantic siblings, its versatility, and which
  other axes it bridges.

  FACETS ADDED PER TIER 1 NODE (six):

    1. :associations
       Top-20 co-occurring words by PPMI (Positive Pointwise
       Mutual Information) over ±5-word windows. Reveals the
       signifier's neighborhood — the words that keep company
       with this one.

    2. :distributional-neighbors
       Top-10 words with most-similar surrounding-word
       distributions (cosine similarity over co-occurrence
       vectors). Semantic siblings by USE, not by definition.
       Two words with similar neighbor distributions play
       similar roles in the language.

    3. :context-entropy
       Shannon entropy of the word's ±5-word neighbor
       distribution. High entropy = versatile signifier hub
       (used in many contexts, weaves many topics). Low
       entropy = narrow specialist (locked into one context).
       A diagnostic for graph-integration weight.

    4. :idf
       Inverse-document-frequency across corpus files.
       Distinctiveness measure — complements raw frequency.
       A word can be common overall but concentrated in few
       documents (high IDF) or spread evenly across the corpus
       (low IDF). Both are meaningful signals.

    5. :tf-idf-per-axis
       Where the word is most emblematic — which axis (or which
       book within an axis) has this word's TF-IDF weight
       peak. Reveals axis-anchoring: 'kindness' peaks in
       Feeling books, 'algorithm' peaks in Intuition books.
       If a word peaks in an axis DIFFERENT from its assigned
       axis, that's a signal to review the axis classification.

    6. :cross-axis-bridge-score
       Count of :associations that fall in axes OTHER than the
       word's own axis. High bridge-score = the word weaves
       multiple axes together (LOAD-BEARING for graph
       integration — bridge words are the connective tissue
       of the four-axis system).

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/classified.tsv (restricted to Tier 1)
    Plus raw corpus files (rescanned for co-occurrence counting):
      scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl
      Scheme/reference/*.slat

  OUTPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/enrichment/tier1-associative.jsonl
      One JSON blob per Tier 1 word, merged into the seed-list-
      to-graph pipeline at Step 8 (node authoring). Schema:
        {
          'word': ...,
          'axis': ...,
          'associations': [{'neighbor': ..., 'ppmi': ...}, ...],
          'distributional_neighbors': [{'word': ...,
                                        'cosine': ...}, ...],
          'context_entropy': ...,
          'idf': ...,
          'tf_idf_per_axis': {'sensation': ..., ...,
                              'peak_axis': ...},
          'cross_axis_bridge_score': ...
        }

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06b-enrich.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    import json, re
    from collections import Counter, defaultdict
    from math import log2, sqrt
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
    IN   = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut/classified.tsv'
    OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/enrichment/tier1-associative.jsonl'
    OUT.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    WINDOW = 5

    # Load Tier 1 vocab and their axes
    tier1 = {}   # word -> axis
    axis_of = {} # word -> axis
    with IN.open() as f:
        for line in f:
            axis, word, freq, *_ = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
            if axis == 'other':
                continue
            tier1[word] = axis
            axis_of[word] = axis

    # File-to-axis mapping: group corpus files by their axis anchor
    # (books-of-values → feeling; book-of-motion → sensation; etc.)
    # This map is authored once and pinned into the runlog.
    FILE_AXIS = {
        # 'scheme-books/book-of-values/*': 'feeling',
        # ... populate per canonical run ...
    }
    def axis_of_file(rel_path):
        for pat, ax in FILE_AXIS.items():
            if Path(rel_path).match(pat):
                return ax
        return None  # unclassified files contribute to no axis

    GLOBS = [
        'scheme-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
        'word-books/book-of-*/*.book.slatl',
        'Scheme/reference/*.slat',
    ]
    TOK = re.compile(r'[a-z]+')

    # Pass 1: co-occurrence counts + per-file counts + total tokens
    cooc = defaultdict(Counter)     # word -> Counter(neighbor -> count)
    word_count = Counter()          # word -> total occurrences
    doc_count = Counter()           # word -> # files it appears in
    per_axis_tf = defaultdict(Counter)  # axis -> Counter(word -> count)
    n_docs = 0
    total_tokens = 0

    for glob in GLOBS:
        for path in ROOT.glob(glob):
            n_docs += 1
            rel = str(path.relative_to(ROOT))
            file_axis = axis_of_file(rel)
            text = path.read_text(errors='replace').lower()
            toks = TOK.findall(text)
            total_tokens += len(toks)
            seen_here = set()
            for i, w in enumerate(toks):
                if w not in tier1:
                    continue
                word_count[w] += 1
                seen_here.add(w)
                lo = max(0, i - WINDOW)
                hi = min(len(toks), i + WINDOW + 1)
                for j in range(lo, hi):
                    if j == i:
                        continue
                    cooc[w][toks[j]] += 1
                if file_axis:
                    per_axis_tf[file_axis][w] += 1
            for w in seen_here:
                doc_count[w] += 1

    # PPMI
    def ppmi(joint, x_count, y_count, total):
        if joint <= 0 or x_count <= 0 or y_count <= 0:
            return 0.0
        p_xy = joint / total
        p_x  = x_count / total
        p_y  = y_count / total
        pmi  = log2(p_xy / (p_x * p_y))
        return max(pmi, 0.0)

    def shannon_entropy(counter):
        total = sum(counter.values())
        if total <= 0: return 0.0
        return -sum((c/total) * log2(c/total)
                    for c in counter.values() if c > 0)

    # Neighbor totals (needed for PPMI marginal)
    neighbor_total = Counter()
    for w, ctr in cooc.items():
        for n, c in ctr.items():
            neighbor_total[n] += c
    cooc_total = sum(neighbor_total.values())

    # Pass 2: per-word top-20 PPMI associations
    associations = {}
    for w, ctr in cooc.items():
        scored = []
        for n, c in ctr.items():
            s = ppmi(c, word_count.get(w, 0),
                     neighbor_total.get(n, 0), cooc_total)
            if s > 0:
                scored.append((n, s))
        scored.sort(key=lambda t: -t[1])
        associations[w] = scored[:20]

    # Distributional neighbors: cosine over cooc vectors of Tier 1 words
    def cos(a, b):
        keys = set(a) | set(b)
        dot = sum(a.get(k, 0) * b.get(k, 0) for k in keys)
        na  = sqrt(sum(v*v for v in a.values()))
        nb  = sqrt(sum(v*v for v in b.values()))
        if na == 0 or nb == 0: return 0.0
        return dot / (na * nb)

    dist_neighbors = {}
    words_list = list(cooc.keys())
    for w in words_list:
        scored = []
        for other in words_list:
            if other == w: continue
            s = cos(cooc[w], cooc[other])
            if s > 0:
                scored.append((other, s))
        scored.sort(key=lambda t: -t[1])
        dist_neighbors[w] = scored[:10]

    # Emit
    with OUT.open('w') as f:
        for w, axis in tier1.items():
            assocs = associations.get(w, [])
            # cross-axis-bridge = count of associations in other axes
            bridge = sum(1 for n, _ in assocs
                         if n in axis_of and axis_of[n] != axis)
            entropy = shannon_entropy(cooc.get(w, Counter()))
            df = doc_count.get(w, 0)
            idf = log2(n_docs / df) if df > 0 else 0.0
            # tf-idf per axis: for each axis, tf(w in axis) * idf
            tfidf_axis = {}
            for ax in ('sensation', 'intuition',
                       'thinking', 'feeling'):
                tfidf_axis[ax] = per_axis_tf[ax].get(w, 0) * idf
            peak_axis = max(tfidf_axis.items(), key=lambda kv: kv[1])[0]
            tfidf_axis['peak_axis'] = peak_axis

            f.write(json.dumps({
                'word': w,
                'axis': axis,
                'associations': [{'neighbor': n, 'ppmi': round(s, 4)}
                                 for n, s in assocs],
                'distributional_neighbors':
                    [{'word': other, 'cosine': round(s, 4)}
                     for other, s in dist_neighbors.get(w, [])],
                'context_entropy':         round(entropy, 4),
                'idf':                     round(idf, 4),
                'tf_idf_per_axis':         tfidf_axis,
                'cross_axis_bridge_score': bridge,
            }) + '\\n')

    print(f'enriched {len(tier1)} Tier 1 words; wrote {OUT}')

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06b-enrich.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  WALL-TIME ESTIMATE:
    Minutes for ~1000 Tier 1 words on the current Motoi corpus
    (~856 files, ~1.5M tokens). The distributional-neighbors
    pass is O(|V|^2) over Tier 1 only, so keep the pool bounded
    (Pareto cut already does this). Cheap.

  OUTPUT USE:
    The JSONL blob merges into Step 8 node authoring. Each Tier 1
    :node-<word> entry gains six new fields from its matching
    blob. Node authoring joins on :word.

  REPEATABILITY GUARANTEE:
    All six facets are deterministic functions of (corpus files,
    Tier 1 word set, file-to-axis map). No LLM in this step. No
    randomness. Rerun on the same inputs produces byte-identical
    output. Rerun on an updated corpus produces same-shape output
    with semantically meaningful drift (associations shift as
    authors write new chapters; bridge-scores rise as cross-axis
    prose enters the corpus).

  WHY THIS MATTERS (Firth):
    Meaning derives from patterns of use. Distributional-hypothesis-
    lite. Gives every Tier 1 node a neighborhood, semantic siblings,
    a versatility measure, an axis anchor, and cross-axis bridges.
    Without this, graph nodes are isolated definitions; with it,
    they form a real semantic network — the graph earns its name.

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] tier1-associative.jsonl row count = Tier 1 vocabulary
        size (every Tier 1 word gets an entry).
    [ ] Every entry has all six facets present. No missing keys.
    [ ] Spot-check 20 random words: :associations top-3 should
        look semantically related to the target word. If
        'kindness' associates with 'algorithm' and 'compile', the
        tokenizer, window, or corpus-axis map is broken.
    [ ] :cross-axis-bridge-score distribution has a healthy tail
        (some low, some high). If all scores are 0, axis
        classification is trivially confined; if all scores are
        20, axis boundaries are meaningless.
    [ ] :context-entropy distribution non-degenerate (spans a
        multi-bit range). If all entropies are near-identical,
        the window or corpus is too small.
  """

  :section-7-output-seed-lists
  """
  STEP 6 — OUTPUT PER-AXIS SEED LISTS.

  GOAL: split classified.tsv by axis and produce clean TSV seed
  lists, one per axis, sorted by frequency descending. These files
  are the deliverable of the pipeline and the input to graph
  authoring (Step 8).

  INPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/cut/classified.tsv

  OUTPUTS:
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/sensation.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/intuition.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/thinking.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/feeling.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/other-kept.tsv
      Format for each: freq \\t word  (sorted by freq desc)

    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/MANIFEST.txt
      Row count per axis, total, and top-10 preview per axis, so
      an operator can eyeball the shape without opening each file.

  SCRIPT SKELETON (scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06-emit-seed-tsv.py):

    #!/usr/bin/env python3
    from collections import defaultdict
    from pathlib import Path

    ROOT = Path('/Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme')
    IN   = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/cut/classified.tsv'
    OUT  = ROOT / 'derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds'
    OUT.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    by_axis = defaultdict(list)  # axis -> list of (freq, word)
    with IN.open() as f:
        for line in f:
            axis, word, freq, *_ = line.rstrip('\\n').split('\\t')
            by_axis[axis].append((int(freq), word))

    manifest = []
    for axis in ('sensation', 'intuition', 'thinking',
                 'feeling', 'other'):
        rows = sorted(by_axis[axis], key=lambda r: (-r[0], r[1]))
        name = 'other-kept' if axis == 'other' else axis
        path = OUT / f'{name}.tsv'
        with path.open('w') as f:
            for freq, word in rows:
                f.write(f'{freq}\\t{word}\\n')
        manifest.append((name, len(rows), rows[:10]))

    with (OUT/'MANIFEST.txt').open('w') as f:
        f.write('axis         count      top-10\\n')
        for name, cnt, top10 in manifest:
            f.write(f'{name:12} {cnt:6d}     '
                    f'{", ".join(w for _, w in top10)}\\n')
        f.write(f'\\ngrand total: '
                f'{sum(c for _, c, _ in manifest)}\\n')

    print('seed lists written to', OUT)

  RUN:
    cd /Users/alfred/code/motoi-scheme
    python3 scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06-emit-seed-tsv.py \\
      | tee -a derived/graph-seeds/RUN-$(date -u +%Y%m%d).log

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] All five TSV files exist.
    [ ] MANIFEST.txt row counts match `wc -l` on each TSV.
    [ ] Grand total in MANIFEST equals classified.tsv row count.
    [ ] Top-10 preview per axis passes the eyeball test.

  DELIVERABLE:
    The five *.tsv files under derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/
    are the pipeline output. Everything after this feeds them
    into graph authoring or CPT extraction; the seed lists
    themselves are done.
  """

  :section-8-gap-fill-authoring
  """
  STEP 7 — OPTIONAL GAP-FILL AUTHORING.

  GOAL: if an axis's Pareto-cut yield is under target for its
  corpus-language balance, propose category-based authoring to
  lift underweight axes back to healthy proportions.

  WHEN TO RUN THIS STEP:
    Compare the MANIFEST.txt counts against target proportions.
    Rough Motoi Mk 1 targets (order-of-magnitude):
      Sensation ≥ ~30% of axis-classified pool (kids and adults
                                                both need concrete
                                                world reference)
      Intuition ~30-40% (concepts, patterns — Motoi's core)
      Thinking  ≥ 10% (invariants, contracts, do-and-dont)
      Feeling   ≥ 5%  (register lexicon — corpus authors tend
                       to under-emit; watch this one)
    If an axis falls below its floor by more than a factor of 2,
    author additional content in that axis's category and rerun
    the pipeline.

  Motoi Mk 1 practice:
    Sensation kids-world nouns underweight → author more
      book-of-motion / book-of-world chapters with concrete
      world entities.
    Feeling adult-register nouns underweight → author more
      book-of-values / book-of-jesse chapters with tonal
      vocabulary.
    Thinking do-and-dont nouns underweight → author more
      book-of-values / book-of-limits chapters with invariant
      + contract vocabulary.

  AUTHORED-NOUN PROVENANCE:
    Authored gap-fill nouns get provenance stamped :authored
    at their book-chapter emission. When the pipeline reruns
    over the enlarged corpus, those nouns must PASS the M≥5
    corpus-recurrence check on their own merits (i.e., they
    must actually appear ≥5 times, which typically means the
    author writes them into 3+ chapters, not one). If a proposed
    gap-fill noun never crosses recurrence threshold, that's
    a signal the author overreached — either integrate the
    noun more, or drop it from the target list.

    HARD RULE (no-contaminants): gap-fill authoring is a HUMAN
    OR AGENT AUTHORING ACT with :authored provenance and
    :source-book-chapter attribution. It is NEVER 'the LLM
    generates a plausible Feeling noun list'. The LLM may
    PROPOSE candidate categories to author (e.g., 'Motoi lacks
    grief-register vocabulary; propose 10 grief-related nouns
    to introduce via book-of-values ch 8'); an author decides
    which to accept and writes them into book chapters. Then
    they earn a graph node through Pareto recurrence on the
    NEXT pipeline run — not on this one.

  OUTPUT:
    derived/graph-seeds/gap-fill/proposals-<date>.md
      Human-readable list of proposed categories per underweight
      axis, with example vocabulary, target chapter, and target
      book. Reviewed by Alfred.

  DO NOT DIRECTLY EDIT axis-seeds/*.tsv to add authored nouns.
  That breaks the derivation-from-corpus invariant. Nouns arrive
  in the seed list by RUNNING THIS PIPELINE, not by hand-editing
  its output.
  """

  :section-9-feed-into-graph
  """
  STEP 8 — FEED SEED LISTS INTO THE JUNG-AXIS GRAPHS.

  GOAL: turn each surviving word into a graph node under the
  matching axis graph, populating JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA
  fields (universal + axis-specific + dialogue + cross-refs).

  INPUTS:
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/sensation.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/intuition.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/thinking.tsv
    derived/graph-seeds/axis-seeds/feeling.tsv

  OUTPUTS:
    graphs/graph-of-sensation.slat
    graphs/graph-of-intuition.slat
    graphs/graph-of-thinking.slat
    graphs/graph-of-feeling.slat

  Each output SLAT file is a (slat-set ...) containing one
  :node-<word> entry per seed-list row. The node schema is
  defined in engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat and
  authored fields per node include (at minimum):
    · :signifier     — the word itself
    · :axis          — the axis this node belongs to
    · :signified     — 1-3 sentence concept content
    · :dialogue      — per-node dialogue field (see
                       memory/project_signifier_signified_and_dialogue)
    · :evidence      — 3-5 corpus excerpts showing the word in use
    · :cross-refs    — related nodes in same axis or other axes
    · :cpt-shape-plan— which shapes from chapter 4 § catalog will
                       verbalize this node
    · :provenance    — 'derived: pipeline-run <date>'
    · :first-observed-freq — the Pareto-cut frequency at the
                       time the node was added

  TIERED TREATMENT (2-tier system, per Alfred 2026-07-20;
  Tier 1 selection rule sharpened per Alfred 2026-07-21):

    Every corpus content-word is covered by exactly one tier.
    Tier reflects IMPORTANCE for structured graph treatment; it
    does NOT reflect inclusion (both tiers ARE included in the
    graph substrate).

    · Tier 1 (~1,200 words: TF-IDF TOP-300 PER AXIS, doc-freq ≥5):
        CANONICAL SELECTION RULE (supersedes prior "per-axis Pareto"
        rule, per Alfred 2026-07-21):
          For each of the 4 Jung axes, take the top-300 words
          ranked by TF-IDF within that axis, subject to the
          filter doc-freq ≥ 5 (word must appear in at least 5
          distinct corpus files). Estimated ~1,200 words total
          (Sensation 300 · Intuition 300 · Thinking 300 ·
          Feeling ~300 — smaller if an axis has fewer than 300
          words meeting the doc-freq filter).
        WHY TF-IDF over per-axis Pareto:
          Pareto cut selects VERSATILE workhorse glue (high raw
          frequency, low distinctiveness). TF-IDF selects
          DISTINCTIVE axis-signature vocabulary — the words
          that ARE that axis. Empirical finding (2026-07-20
          Motoi run): top-20 TF-IDF and top-20 entropy per axis
          have ZERO overlap. Entropy names the workhorses;
          TF-IDF names the axis signatures. Tier 1 wants the
          latter. See § 9b for full rationale.
        WHY doc-freq ≥ 5:
          Single-file or 2-file spikes are TF-IDF artifacts, not
          semantic signals. The floor ensures every Tier 1 word
          has demonstrated presence across the corpus, not
          within one author's or one book's local vocabulary.
        FULL node treatment INCLUDING Step 6b associative
        enrichment. Every Tier 1 node has all schema fields
        populated per § 9b (5 categories: Identity · Context-of-
        use · Relations/interconnections · Statistical metadata ·
        Provenance+governance) PLUS axis-specific facets AND
        all six associative facets:
          :associations, :distributional-neighbors,
          :context-entropy, :idf, :tf-idf-per-axis,
          :cross-axis-bridge-score.
        These are the graph's load-bearing nodes — the words
        the model MUST reify because they carry axis identity
        and drive the corpus's semantic gravity.

    · Tier 2 (~24,300 stubs — every other corpus content-word):
        LIGHTWEIGHT REGISTRY STUB. Stubs carry only:
          :canonical                  — the word itself
          :source-refs                — files/lines where it appears
          :tier                       — literal 'tier-2'
          :first-appears-in-book-count — number of distinct books
                                        the word occurs in
        No axis assignment. No PPMI. No :distributional-neighbors.
        No :context-entropy. No :tf-idf-per-axis. Registry-only
        entries — the graph knows they exist, knows where they
        appear, knows how widely they spread, and NOTHING ELSE.

    NO MIDDLE TIER. Alfred 2026-07-20 explicitly collapsed the
    prior 3-tier scheme to 2 tiers. If any operator finds
    themselves wanting a 'Tier 2 with partial enrichment' or
    'Tier 3 stub' distinction, the answer is NO — promote to
    Tier 1 via the TF-IDF top-300-per-axis mechanism (author
    more corpus in the target axis until the word's per-axis
    TF-IDF cracks the top 300 AND doc-freq ≥ 5) or leave as
    Tier 2 stub. The tier boundary IS the TF-IDF top-300 rule
    (per Alfred 2026-07-21; supersedes earlier 'boundary IS
    the Pareto cut' rule).

    RATIONALE:
      · PPMI computation is cheap but MEANINGFUL only for high-
        recurrence words. Tier 2 words have freq < f_thresh
        (post-Pareto) or fail the TF-IDF-per-axis / doc-freq
        thresholds → PPMI is statistically noisy → provides no
        reliable semantic signal. Save compute + storage for
        where it matters.
      · A middle tier tempts operators to draft partial
        enrichment ('just associations, skip entropy'), which
        drifts. Two crisp tiers = no drift.
      · If a Tier 2 stub earns axis-signature recurrence on a
        future rerun (its per-axis TF-IDF cracks the top 300
        AND doc-freq ≥ 5), it is PROMOTED to Tier 1 and Step 6b
        enriches it in that later pipeline pass. Tier 2 → Tier 1
        promotion is the ONLY tier movement supported; demotion
        does not happen (nodes only accumulate history).
      · Every corpus content-word is covered. No word is silently
        dropped — either it's a Tier 1 load-bearing node or a
        Tier 2 registry stub. The registry stub matters: it
        prevents future operators from thinking a word is
        'unknown' when it is in fact 'known but rare'.

  NODE AUTHORING IS ITS OWN AGENT-LANE. This chapter (05) delivers
  the SEED LISTS. Node authoring is downstream and follows
  engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat plus a per-axis
  authoring runbook that will be shipped in a later SRE chapter.

  DOWNSTREAM: once nodes are authored, they feed CPT extraction
  per SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-type.slat
  § material graph-{axis} — S20, S21, S22, S23 shapes verbalize
  each node into extractable CPT documents.

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] Every row in each seed TSV has a corresponding :node-*
        entry in the matching graph SLAT.
    [ ] Every node has all required schema fields present.
    [ ] Every node's :evidence excerpts point to real corpus
        lines that still exist (post-corpus-drift).
  """

  :section-9b-tier-1-node-schema
  """
  STEP 8b — FULL TIER 1 NODE SCHEMA (5 CATEGORIES).

  Authored per Alfred 2026-07-21 directive. This is the CANONICAL
  Tier 1 node schema for graph node authoring. Every Tier 1 node
  MUST populate every applicable field. Missing fields are
  authoring debt, tracked and closed before fold-eligibility.

  MIRROR: this section is repeated verbatim in
  engineering/WEAVE-RECIPE.slat § section-cpt-shapes-catalog Tier 1
  spec. Redundancy is deliberate — any LLM walking into either
  document must reach the same schema from disk alone.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  UNIVERSAL FIELDS — every Tier 1 node, all 4 axes.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CATEGORY 1 — IDENTITY.

    :id
        Namespaced identifier. Form '<axis>/<canonical>'.
        Example: 'intuition/recursion', 'thinking/invariant'.

    :canonical
        The naked signifier — the word as it appears in the
        corpus, no namespacing.

    :synonyms
        Alternative signifiers that refer to the same node.
        List of strings. Not translation, not analogy — actual
        synonymy in the Motoi register.

    :definition
        One-sentence meaning. Register: kid-accessible-through-
        adult-nuanced. Ships to child readers unchanged, holds
        up to adult scrutiny.

  CATEGORY 2 — CONTEXT-OF-USE.

    :examples
        3-5 story snippets showing the word in the Motoi sense.
        Prose fragments, each 1-3 sentences.

    :example-dialogue
        2-3 line talk-and-response with the word in actual use.
        Structured as ((:speaker <sp> :line <text>) ...).

    :used-in-programs-as
        How the word appears in Motoi CODE — the bridge from
        signifier to base action. E.g. 'a :contract field on
        a verb entry', 'a test that must pass', 'a keyword in
        a macro form'.

    :appears-in-corpus
        Top source-file refs where the word actually recurs.
        Structured pointers ((:book <b> :chapter <c>)
        (:file <path>)). Populated by scanner, not by author.

  CATEGORY 3 — RELATIONS / INTERCONNECTIONS.

    :cross-refs-books
        Book chapters where the word appears. Scanner-populated.
        Distinct from :appears-in-corpus in granularity:
        :appears-in-corpus is per-file evidence, :cross-refs-
        books is per-book aggregation for navigation.

    :cross-refs-graph
        Other Jung-axis nodes this node connects to. Explicit
        graph edges: ((:ref-graph <axis> :ref-id <id>) ...).

    :associations
        Top-20 co-occurring words by PPMI (Positive Pointwise
        Mutual Information) over ±5-word windows. Corpus-
        derived, deterministic. Populated by Step 6b.

    :distributional-neighbors
        Top-10 words with similar surrounding-word distributions
        (cosine over co-occurrence vectors). Semantic siblings
        by USE. Populated by Step 6b.

    :oppositions
        Greimas semiotic-square antonyms / complementaries.
        Words that define this node by contrast (what it is by
        what it is NOT). Authored, not derived.

    :cross-axis-bridge-score
        Count of :associations that fall in axes OTHER than this
        node's own axis. Bridge-word marker. Populated by Step
        6b. High score = LOAD-BEARING connective tissue.

  CATEGORY 4 — STATISTICAL METADATA.

    :freq
        Total token count in the corpus.

    :doc-freq
        Number of distinct files containing the word. Must be
        ≥ 5 for Tier 1 eligibility.

    :tf-idf
        The TF-IDF score that got the word into Tier 1. Top-300
        per axis are Tier 1.

    :context-entropy
        Shannon entropy of the neighbor distribution. Versatility
        measure. High = workhorse; low = specialist.

    :idf
        Inverse-document-frequency across corpus files.
        Distinctiveness measure.

    :tf-idf-per-axis
        Where TF-IDF weight peaks by axis. Structured as
        ((:axis <a> :peak-weight <n>) (:axis <b> :secondary
        <n>) ...). Axis-anchoring signal. If peak axis differs
        from the node's assigned axis, review classification.

  CATEGORY 5 — PROVENANCE + GOVERNANCE.

    :provenance
        Source + lane + date. Structured as
        ((:source <s> :lane <l> :date <d>) ...).

    :tier
        Literal '1' (or '2' for stubs). Tier 1 nodes are the
        target of this schema.

    :kid-friendly
        Boolean annotation. NOT a gate — Tier 1 words that read
        unfriendly still ship if training-eligible; the flag
        aids downstream selection.

    :training-eligible
        Boolean. Must be #t to fold. Set #f only for nodes
        under review, embargo, or awaiting Priya cosign.

    :dialect
        Literal 'motoi' (or 'sakura' for the downstream repo's
        parallel graph).

    :audience
        Governance metadata. :any / :child / :adult / :operator.

    :content-rating
        Governance metadata. :G / :PG / :adult.

    :confidentiality
        Governance metadata. :public / :internal /
        :priya-cosign.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  AXIS-SPECIFIC FACETS — one block per node based on its axis.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  SENSATION-axis nodes add:
    :category
        animal / plant / place / tool / material / food /
        body-part / weather / celestial / etc.
    :sensory-description
        1-3 sentence sensory sketch (sight, sound, touch, smell,
        taste) — the felt-shape of the referent.
    :where-found
        Environmental context. 'in a kitchen', 'in the forest'.
    :size-scale
        :hand / :body / :room / :landscape / :cosmic.
    :kid-familiarity
        :household / :common / :specialist / :rare.
    :used-in-programs-as
        (Already universal; sensation nodes still populate.)

  INTUITION-axis nodes add:
    :category
        concept / pattern / algorithm / relation.
    :definition-technical
        Second definition tuned for adult-technical reader; sits
        beside the universal :definition (which is kid-through-
        adult). Both ship.
    :example-in-scheme
        Runnable Motoi code demonstrating the concept. MUST run
        under ./bin/motoi.
    :example-in-world
        Sensation-axis analogy. Bridges intuition to concrete.
    :prerequisites
        Nodes the reader must know first. List of :ref-id.
    :appears-in-books
        Books that treat the concept in depth (learning /
        application / composition / introspection / prose /
        challenge). Distinct from :cross-refs-books which is
        exhaustive; :appears-in-books is the curated top-5.

  THINKING-axis nodes add:
    :principle-kind
        :safety / :correctness / :honesty / :boundary /
        :prohibition.
    :short-scenario
        Story where the principle is at play. 2-5 sentences.
    :antipattern-scenario
        Story of violation + consequence. 2-5 sentences.
    :related-verbs
        ((:ref-file <path> :ref-verb <name>) ...) — verbs
        whose contract embodies this principle.
    :motoi-behavior
        What Motoi DOES when the principle is invoked. 1-3
        sentences. Concrete, testable.
    :related-books
        Books teaching this principle. Top-5 curated.

  FEELING-axis nodes add:
    :register-kind
        :calm / :urgency / :warmth / :dryness / :silence /
        :care / :playfulness.
    :example-dialogue
        (Already universal; feeling nodes emphasize register in
        the dialogue exchange itself.)
    :motoi-uses-when
        Conditions under which Motoi selects this register.
        List of trigger patterns.
    :contrast-register
        What this register ISN'T. Named contrast to sharpen
        boundaries. E.g. warmth's contrast-register might be
        :formality.
    :related-principles
        Thinking-axis principles this register serves.
        ((:ref-graph 'thinking' :ref-id ...) ...).
    :related-books
        Books demonstrating the register.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WORKED EXAMPLE (thinking/invariant) — verbatim, canonical.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (node
    ;; Identity
    :id                    \"thinking/invariant\"
    :canonical             \"invariant\"
    :synonyms              (\"unchanging-property\" \"always-holds\")
    :definition            \"A property that stays true no matter what else changes. A rule the code promises to keep, forever.\"

    ;; Context-of-use
    :examples              (\"The invariant of `map` is that the output list has exactly the same length as the input list.\"
                            \"If you break an invariant, the program lies. Motoi treats broken invariants as bugs to hunt.\")
    :example-dialogue      ((:speaker :child    :line \"What if the list is empty?\")
                            (:speaker :motoi    :line \"The invariant still holds — length zero in, length zero out. That IS the property.\"))
    :used-in-programs-as   (\"A :contract field on a verb entry\"
                            \"An assertion inside a function body\"
                            \"A test that must pass for every input\")
    :appears-in-corpus     ((:book \"book-of-scheme-one\" :chapter \"13-invariants-and-proof\")
                            (:book \"book-of-composition\" :chapter \"05-contracts\")
                            (:file \"Scheme/reference/01-core.slat\"))

    ;; Relations / interconnections
    :cross-refs-graph      ((:ref-graph \"thinking\" :ref-id \"thinking/proof\")
                            (:ref-graph \"thinking\" :ref-id \"thinking/contract\")
                            (:ref-graph \"intuition\" :ref-id \"intuition/property\"))
    :associations          (\"proof(0.87)\" \"contract(0.71)\" \"property(0.68)\" \"test(0.65)\"
                            \"holds(0.61)\" \"always(0.58)\" \"claim(0.55)\" \"verify(0.52)\")
    :distributional-neighbors (\"property\" \"contract\" \"guarantee\" \"claim\" \"law\")
    :oppositions           (\"counterexample\" \"regression\" \"drift\" \"bug\")
    :cross-axis-bridge-score 3

    ;; Statistical metadata
    :freq                  2606
    :doc-freq              89
    :tf-idf                756.4
    :context-entropy       0.94
    :idf                   2.28
    :tf-idf-per-axis       ((:axis \"thinking\" :peak-weight 756.4)
                            (:axis \"intuition\" :secondary 214.1))

    ;; Axis-specific (Thinking)
    :principle-kind        :correctness
    :short-scenario        \"A child writes a program that reverses a list. Motoi asks: 'What always stays true, no matter what list you give it?' The child sees: the length doesn't change. That's the invariant.\"
    :antipattern-scenario  \"The child changes the code and the reversed list ends up longer than the original. Motoi points at the invariant: 'This property is broken. Length must stay the same. Find the extra element.'\"
    :related-verbs         ((:ref-file \"Scheme/reference/01-core.slat\" :ref-verb \"assert/invariant\")
                            (:ref-file \"Scheme/reference/07-testing.slat\" :ref-verb \"test/property\"))
    :motoi-behavior        \"When Motoi sees an assertion labeled invariant, it treats a violation as blocking. It won't hand-wave. The property is the promise.\"

    ;; Provenance + governance
    :provenance            ((:source \"corpus-derived\" :lane \"reclassifier-v2\" :date \"2026-07-21\"))
    :tier                  \"1\"
    :kid-friendly          #t
    :training-eligible     #t
    :dialect               \"motoi\"
    :audience              :any
    :content-rating        :G
    :confidentiality       :public)

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TF-IDF vs ENTROPY — WHY TF-IDF WINS FOR TIER 1 SELECTION.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Both statistics are cheap, both are derived from the corpus,
  both name 'important' words — but they name DIFFERENT
  importance.

  · Context-entropy names WORKHORSE GLUE.
      High-entropy words appear in a huge variety of neighbor
      contexts. They are the connective tissue of the language
      — 'the', 'has', 'with', 'value', 'list'. They keep prose
      moving. They do not carry axis identity. If you pick a
      graph node's axis by asking 'where does this word appear',
      workhorse words give a shrug.

  · TF-IDF names AXIS-SIGNATURE VOCABULARY.
      High TF-IDF words are frequent within an axis's corpus
      slice AND rare outside it. They are the words that ARE
      that axis — 'chlorophyll' for Sensation, 'recursion' for
      Intuition, 'invariant' for Thinking, 'warmth' for Feeling.
      Pick these as graph nodes and the graph carries axis
      semantics into the model.

  EMPIRICAL FINDING (2026-07-20 Motoi run, cited by Alfred):
    Top-20 TF-IDF and top-20 entropy per axis have ZERO
    overlap. Entropy top-20 is workhorse glue; TF-IDF top-20
    is axis signature. The two rankings are orthogonal on
    this corpus. Choosing entropy would populate the graph
    with 'value', 'thing', 'has', 'list' — words the base
    model already knows and words that carry no axis signal.
    Choosing TF-IDF populates the graph with words that BOTH
    the model needs to learn AND that carry axis identity.

  RULE:
    Tier 1 selection = TF-IDF top-300 per axis, filtered by
    doc-freq ≥ 5. Nothing else. Not Pareto (that's the entry
    filter). Not entropy (that's a facet — populated per node,
    not used for selection). TF-IDF, top-300, per axis,
    doc-freq floor.

  DOC-FREQ FLOOR RATIONALE:
    A word that appears 500 times in one file has a huge
    TF-IDF spike because it's rare across files. That's a
    single-author artifact, not corpus vocabulary. The floor
    (≥ 5 distinct files) filters these out. Empirically the
    floor removes ~5-10% of top-TF-IDF-per-axis candidates
    without touching any word a competent reviewer would keep.

  IF AN AXIS HAS FEWER THAN 300 QUALIFIED WORDS:
    Take all qualified words (do not lower the doc-freq floor
    to inflate the count). A short axis is a signal about
    corpus coverage, not a signal to weaken the selection
    rule. Feeling-axis in the current Motoi corpus may hit
    this — document the shortfall in the run log and treat
    as an authoring gap (Step 8 gap-fill lane).

  VERIFICATION:
    [ ] Per-axis Tier 1 count is ≤ 300 and every included
        word has doc-freq ≥ 5.
    [ ] Every Tier 1 node has all 5 category blocks present
        with all applicable fields populated (schema above).
    [ ] Every Tier 1 node has the axis-specific facet block
        for its assigned axis.
    [ ] Worked-example round-trip: a canonical Tier 1 node
        (recommended: thinking/invariant) can be re-emitted
        from disk by the authoring pipeline byte-identical to
        the example above (modulo :appears-in-corpus which
        tracks corpus drift).
  """

  :section-three-tier-doctrine
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  THREE-TIER DOCTRINE (Alfred 2026-07-21).
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  SUPERSEDES the '2-tier only' text in § 9. The prior 2-tier framing
  (Tier 1 rich · Tier 2 stub) collapsed the middle-band connectors
  and modifiers into either full enrichment or bare registry — losing
  the semantic-connective-tissue layer that Firth-distributional
  models require. Alfred 2026-07-21 authorized a three-tier system
  with an explicit function-word EXCLUSION set. Every corpus
  content-word lands in exactly one of Tier 1 / Tier 2 / Tier 3.
  Function words are excluded from the graph entirely.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 1 — PRIMARY SIGNIFIERS. ~1,200 words (300/axis · 4 axes).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Primary signifiers · topic-markers · axis-signature vocabulary.
    Words that tell you what a document is ABOUT. When a Tier 1
    word appears, the reader (and the model) can infer the axis
    the passage lives on. 'chlorophyll' says Sensation; 'recursion'
    says Intuition; 'invariant' says Thinking; 'warmth' says
    Feeling. These are the load-bearing lexical anchors of Motoi's
    four-axis substrate — the words that ARE the axis.

  SELECTION RULE.
    TF-IDF top-300 per axis, filtered by doc-freq ≥ 5.
    · TF-IDF computed per Jung axis (files tagged into axes by
      the FILE_AXIS map in Step 6b).
    · The ≥ 5 doc-freq filter prevents narrow one-off spikes
      from a single author's local vocabulary from taking a
      Tier 1 slot. Single-file specialists appear frequently in
      that file (high TF) and nowhere else (huge IDF spike) →
      artificially high TF-IDF. The floor kills these.
    · If an axis has fewer than 300 words meeting the filter,
      take all qualified words. Do NOT lower the doc-freq floor.
      A short axis is a signal about corpus coverage (Step 8
      gap-fill lane), not a signal to weaken the selection rule.

  TREATMENT.
    Full 5-category node per § 9b:
      · IDENTITY (:id, :canonical, :synonyms, :definition)
      · CONTEXT-OF-USE (:examples, :example-dialogue,
        :used-in-programs-as, :appears-in-corpus)
      · RELATIONS (:cross-refs-books, :cross-refs-graph,
        :associations, :distributional-neighbors, :oppositions,
        :cross-axis-bridge-score)
      · STATISTICAL METADATA (:freq, :doc-freq, :tf-idf,
        :context-entropy, :idf, :tf-idf-per-axis)
      · PROVENANCE + GOVERNANCE (:provenance, :tier '1',
        :kid-friendly, :training-eligible, :dialect, :audience,
        :content-rating, :confidentiality)
    Plus axis-specific facets per assigned axis (Sensation adds
    :category / :sensory-description / :where-found / :size-scale /
    :kid-familiarity; Intuition adds :category / :definition-
    technical / :example-in-scheme / :example-in-world /
    :prerequisites / :appears-in-books; Thinking adds :principle-
    kind / :short-scenario / :antipattern-scenario / :related-
    verbs / :motoi-behavior / :related-books; Feeling adds
    :register-kind / :motoi-uses-when / :contrast-register /
    :related-principles / :related-books).
    Authoring lane: Sonnet-authored dialogue, oppositions,
    scenarios. Definitions and examples pass Priya cosign for
    kid-friendliness governance.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    SEMIOTICS — signifier taxonomy.
      · Peirce, C.S. Collected Papers vol II (1932). Icon/index/
        symbol trichotomy. Tier 1 words function as SYMBOLS
        (arbitrary conventional signs whose meaning derives from
        the code that reads them) — this is why they need
        explicit :definition + :example-dialogue authored: the
        symbol has no natural connection to referent.
      · Saussure, Ferdinand de. Course in General Linguistics
        (Cours de linguistique générale), 1916. Signifier/
        signified dyad; meaning arises from difference within a
        system. Tier 1's :oppositions facet operationalizes 'a
        sign's value comes from what it is NOT' — every Tier 1
        node names its Greimas-square complementaries so the
        model learns the word by contrast, not just by
        definition.
      · Greimas, A.J. Sémantique structurale (1966); Du sens
        (1970). Semiotic square: contrariety / contradiction /
        implication over a S1/S2/~S1/~S2 quadrangle. Tier 1's
        :oppositions facet IS the Greimas square applied per
        node (S1 = the word; S2 = its opposition; ~S1 =
        privation; ~S2 = the complementary term).

    JUNG PSYCHOLOGICAL TYPES — the four axes.
      · Jung, C.G. Psychologische Typen (1921); Collected Works
        vol. 6, Princeton UP English translation (1971). The
        four functions (Sensation / Intuition / Thinking /
        Feeling) plus the extraversion/introversion attitudes.
      · Sharp, Daryl. Jung Lexicon: A Primer of Terms and
        Concepts. Inner City Books, Toronto, 1991. Contemporary
        reference framing for the four-function typology.
      NOTE — this is an ADAPTATION, not a straight application.
      Jung classified COGNITIVE PROCESSES (how a person orients
      to information). Motoi classifies CONTENT-WORDS (which
      cognitive function a word primarily engages) — Sensation
      words engage the concrete-referent function, Intuition
      words engage the pattern-recognition function, Thinking
      words engage the judgment function, Feeling words engage
      the register-valuation function. The four-function
      partition survives; the object of classification differs.
      Documented explicitly so no future operator confuses
      Motoi's per-word axis-assignment with a Jung-typology
      diagnostic for the reader.

    TF-IDF DISTINCTIVENESS — canonical IR grounding.
      · Sparck-Jones, K. 'A statistical interpretation of term
        specificity and its application in retrieval.' Journal
        of Documentation 28(1):11-21, 1972. IDF's original
        derivation — a term's specificity is inversely related
        to the fraction of documents it appears in.
      · Salton, G., Wong, A., Yang, C.S. 'A vector space model
        for automatic indexing.' Communications of the ACM
        18(11):613-620, 1975. The vector-space model that makes
        TF·IDF the standard document-term weighting. Motoi's
        per-axis TF-IDF is a straight application to axis-
        tagged sub-corpora.

    PPMI ASSOCIATIONS — :associations facet.
      · Church, K.W. & Hanks, P. 'Word association norms,
        mutual information, and lexicography.' Computational
        Linguistics 16(1):22-29, 1990. Pointwise mutual
        information as a measure of word association; the
        POSITIVE clamp (PPMI) is the standard downstream
        variant.
      · Bullinaria, J.A. & Levy, J.P. 'Extracting semantic
        representations from word co-occurrence statistics.'
        Behavior Research Methods 39:510-526, 2007. Empirical
        validation of PPMI over ±window co-occurrence.

    DISTRIBUTIONAL-NEIGHBORS — :distributional-neighbors facet.
      · Harris, Zellig S. 'Distributional structure.' Word
        10(2-3):146-162, 1954. The distributional hypothesis:
        linguistic items with similar distributions have
        similar meanings.
      · Turney, P.D. & Pantel, P. 'From frequency to meaning:
        Vector space models of semantics.' JAIR 37:141-188,
        2010. Comprehensive survey of distributional semantics
        techniques — the lineage of the cosine-over-
        cooccurrence-vectors calculation in Step 6b.

    FRAMENET — background for the future :frames facet (not
    yet in schema but reserved).
      · Fillmore, C.J. 'Frame semantics and the nature of
        language.' Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences
        280(1):20-32, 1976.
      · Baker, C.F., Fillmore, C.J., Lowe, J.B. 'The Berkeley
        FrameNet project.' Proc COLING-ACL 1998, pp 86-90.

    WORDNET — lexical-graph lineage.
      · Miller, G.A., Beckwith, R., Fellbaum, C., Gross, D.,
        Miller, K.J. 'Introduction to WordNet: An on-line
        lexical database.' International Journal of
        Lexicography 3(4):235-244, 1990. Motoi's four-axis
        Jung graph is a Motoi-scale WordNet with Jung-typology
        axis structure replacing WordNet's part-of-speech and
        hypernym trees.

    ENTITY-GRAPH CPT — :cross-refs-graph verbalization.
      · Yang, Z., et al. 'Synthetic continued pretraining.'
        arXiv:2409.07431, 2024. EntiGraph. Verbalizing edges
        between named entities as connective CPT text yields
        log-linear scaling in downstream QA. Motoi's Tier 1
        nodes' :cross-refs-graph edges feed EntiGraph-shape
        S14/S22 CPT verbalization.

    MULTI-SHAPE CPT REQUIREMENT — why 5 categories not 1.
      · Ovadia, O., et al. 'Fine-tuning or retrieval? Comparing
        knowledge injection in LLMs.' arXiv:2312.05934, 2023.
        Unsupervised fine-tuning on canonical-only text fails
        to inject facts; multi-shape presentation is what
        works. Tier 1's five-category treatment is the
        substrate-side of this finding — each Tier 1 word gets
        multiple shape presentations during CPT because it
        has multiple facets that can be verbalized.

    5-PARAPHRASE ATTACHMENT — CPT presentation shape count.
      · Allen-Zhu, Z. & Li, Y. 'Physics of Language Models:
        Part 3.1, Knowledge Storage and Extraction.'
        arXiv:2309.14316, 2023. Empirical elbow at M≈5
        paraphrases per fact for extraction to become
        reliable (9.7% → 96.6% QA). Every Tier 1 CPT shape
        gets 5 paraphrases per the S00 universal wrapper in
        WEAVE-RECIPE.

    REVERSAL CURSE — reversed-shape requirement.
      · Berglund, L., et al. 'The reversal curse: LLMs trained
        on A is B fail to learn B is A.' arXiv:2309.12288, 2023.
        Documents the failure mode. Every Tier 1 fact
        (word → definition) must have its reverse (definition
        → word) authored explicitly.
      · Golovneva, O., et al. 'Reverse training to nurse the
        reversal curse.' arXiv:2403.13799, 2024. Reverse-token
        pretraining as a mitigation; Motoi uses the pair-side
        equivalent (author both directions) rather than the
        token-reversal side.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 2 — CONNECTORS / MODIFIERS / NEIGHBORS.
  ~2,500 words per axis-relevant band, deduplicated.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Semantic connective tissue. Words that give Tier 1 words
    their CONTEXT-OF-USE. If Tier 1 is 'what a document is
    about', Tier 2 is 'how the document says it'. Without
    Tier 2, Tier 1 nodes are isolated topic-markers with no
    grammar of combination. With Tier 2, the model learns
    what Tier 1 words DO in sentences — how they qualify,
    connect, and set register.

  THREE SUB-CHARACTERS WITHIN TIER 2.
    Every Tier 2 word carries a :subchar tag naming which of
    the three roles it plays. A word can carry only one
    :subchar — polysemy across sub-characters resolves to
    dominant use per the Step 5 evidence rule.

    (i) MODIFIERS.
        Adjectives and adverbs that shade Tier 1 nouns with
        qualia. Examples: careful, quickly, gently, distinctly,
        honestly, precisely, tentatively, briskly, plainly.
        Shape Tier 1 nouns/concepts with tonal/precision/
        confidence adjustments.

    (ii) CONNECTORS.
         Relational verbs and prepositions-of-content that
         link Tier 1 in event structures. Examples: holding,
         brings, splits, follows, wraps, feeds, receives,
         crosses. NOT function words ('with', 'of', 'to'
         are function-word-excluded — see below). Connectors
         are content-verbs whose semantic weight lies in the
         relation they establish between Tier 1 nouns.

    (iii) REGISTER-CARRIERS.
          Tonal words that set emotional/tonal frame. Examples:
          together, alone, close, near, calm, gentle, warm,
          quiet, urgent, patient, dry. Carry Feeling-axis
          register without being the register itself (which
          would be Tier 1).

  SELECTION RULE.
    HYBRID union of three sub-lists, deduplicated:
    (a) TF-IDF rank 301-800 per axis (moderate-distinctive
        middle band — the words that are somewhat axis-
        signature but not top-of-signature).
    (b) PPMI-neighbors of Tier 1 not already in Tier 1.
        For each Tier 1 word, take its top-20 PPMI associates
        (:associations facet from § 6b). Any associate that
        isn't already Tier 1 and isn't function-word-excluded
        is a Tier 2 candidate.
    (c) Explicit modifier/register catalog per axis. Authored
        once per axis (~200-400 words per axis) — a curated
        list of adjectives/adverbs/register-carriers the corpus
        actually uses in that axis's prose. Catalog lives at
        scripts/derive-graph-seeds/tier2-catalog-<axis>.txt.
    UNION (a) ∪ (b) ∪ (c), deduplicate, drop function-word
    excluded set, drop Tier 1 members. Estimated ~2,500 words
    total across the axis-relevant band per axis (a Tier 2
    word can carry multiple axis associations; primary-axis
    assignment goes to the axis where the word appears most
    often per PPMI evidence).

  TREATMENT.
    3-field lightweight node — no rich facets, no dialogue,
    no oppositions, no scenarios. Populate only:
      · :definition             one-sentence meaning
      · :context-of-use         1-2 lines describing what
                                Tier 1 words this modifier /
                                connector / register-carrier
                                typically attaches to
      · :relations              top-5 Tier 1 words this word
                                associates with (PPMI-ranked)
    Plus statistical metadata:
      · :freq                   total token count
      · :doc-freq               distinct-file count
      · :tf-idf                 the per-axis TF-IDF value
      · :idf                    inverse document frequency
      · :tier                   literal '2'
      · :subchar                literal 'modifier' /
                                'connector' / 'register-
                                carrier'
    Plus governance:
      · :provenance
      · :training-eligible
      · :dialect                'motoi'
    NO axis-specific rich facets. NO :example-dialogue. NO
    :oppositions. NO :short-scenario. NO :antipattern-
    scenario. Tier 2 is CONTEXT-OF-USE for Tier 1 — not its
    own topic. Authoring lane: Haiku-authored or scripted
    from templates. Sonnet only for spot-review, not for
    body authoring.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    DISTRIBUTIONAL HYPOTHESIS — classical grounding.
      · Firth, J.R. 'A synopsis of linguistic theory,
        1930-1955.' Studies in Linguistic Analysis (Special
        Volume of the Philological Society), Blackwell, Oxford,
        pp 1-32, 1957. Contains the canonical formulation:
        'You shall know a word by the company it keeps.'
        Tier 2 IS the operationalization of this claim — the
        Tier 1 nodes are the target words; Tier 2 words are
        the company they keep. Selection rule (b) is Firth's
        principle applied literally: PPMI-neighbors of every
        Tier 1 word earn Tier 2 status because the
        distributional statistics identify them as the target
        words' semantic company.

    INSTRUCTION-SHAPE DIVERSITY — Only-IF.
      · Zhao, H., et al. 'Only-IF: Revealing the decisive
        effect of instruction diversity on generalization.'
        arXiv:2410.04717, 2024. Instruction-shape diversity
        (not just paraphrase count) is what unlocks
        generalization. Tier 2 provides the CONTEXT variety
        that lets instruction shapes actually vary — a
        question about 'gently' can be asked in dozens of
        constructions because the modifier attaches to many
        Tier 1 nouns. Without Tier 2, instruction diversity
        collapses to Tier 1 permutations only.

    METADATA CONDITIONING — MeCo.
      · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D., et al. 'MeCo: Metadata
        conditioning accelerates language model pre-training.'
        arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. Prepending metadata (URL,
        domain) to every pretraining document yields 33% less
        data for equivalent performance, with a cooldown phase
        (some fraction of docs unprefixed) preserving
        unconditional generation. Tier 2 nodes carry axis and
        sub-character labels that get prepended per MeCo to
        their CPT presentations during Phase 0 (see § section-
        cpt-execution-per-tier Data Type B).

    REPLAY RATIO / DIVERSITY DURING CPT — CMR Scaling Law.
      · Yıldız, C., et al. 'Investigating continual pretraining
        in large language models: Insights and implications.'
        arXiv:2407.17467, 2024. The CMR scaling law for
        continual pretraining shows a 1-10% replay ratio of
        prior data prevents catastrophic forgetting. Tier 2
        provides most of the replay diversity — because
        Tier 2 has more nodes than Tier 1 and appears in
        wider contexts, folding Tier 2 CPT text into the
        stream naturally supplies the corpus variety CMR
        prescribes.

    CROSS-NODE CONTEXT IN ADJACENT TRAINING DOCS — LinkBERT.
      · Yasunaga, M., Leskovec, J., Liang, P. 'LinkBERT:
        Pretraining language models with document links.'
        arXiv:2203.15827, 2022. Placing linked documents in
        the same training context boosts multi-hop reasoning.
        Tier 2 CPT text is authored to reference the Tier 1
        nodes it modifies — 'gently' text mentions 'calm',
        'quietly', 'restraint' (all Tier 1 register nodes) —
        so the Tier 2 doc IS a LinkBERT-style adjacent-node
        context for its Tier 1 anchors.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  TIER 3 — LONG-TAIL LOOKUP / CORPUS-TOKEN REGISTRY.
  ~20,000 words (everything content-word not Tier 1 / Tier 2).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Long-tail lookup · corpus-token registry · anti-confabulation
    aid. Words that appear rarely and in narrow contexts but
    STILL HAVE MEANING — 'Turing', 'quaternion', 'Toledo',
    'entscheidungsproblem'. Not central signifiers (Tier 1) and
    not connectors/modifiers/register (Tier 2), but the model
    should RECOGNIZE them rather than confabulate about them.
    Tier 3 exists so a query mentioning 'Turing' produces
    'yes, that name appears in the ancestry chapter about
    Alonzo Church' rather than an invented biography.

  SELECTION RULE.
    All axis-classified content-words that are NOT Tier 1 or
    Tier 2 AND not a function-word.
    · Script-derived — no judgment, no LLM authoring.
    · Includes proper nouns, technical specifics, once-off
      references, and long-tail rare terms.
    · Does NOT include function words (see EXCLUSION set
      below).
    · Every axis-classified word that fails Tier 1 / Tier 2
      selection but passes the Step 5 axis-classification
      pipeline enters Tier 3.

  TREATMENT.
    3-line SCRIPT-DERIVED stub:
      · :definition             script-inferred from source
                                context (typically first-line
                                or definitional sentence in
                                the source file)
      · :appears-in-corpus      top 3 source-file refs where
                                the word occurs (path + line
                                counts)
      · :surrounding-words      top 10 PPMI co-occurrences
                                (deterministic, from Step 6b
                                enrichment restricted to Tier
                                3 pass)
    Plus:
      · :tier                   literal '3'
      · :axis                   assigned axis (from Step 5)
      · :freq                   total token count
      · :doc-freq               distinct-file count
    NO Sonnet. NO Haiku. NO authoring. Fully mechanical
    script-derivation. Any Tier 3 stub that ends up in a
    training-eligible role must first be PROMOTED to Tier 1
    or Tier 2 through the normal recurrence-driven
    mechanism (author more corpus in the target axis until
    the word crosses a tier boundary on the next pipeline
    rerun).

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    ABSTENTION PAIRS — R-Tuning.
      · Zhang, H., et al. 'R-Tuning: Instructing large
        language models to say ``I don't know''.'
        arXiv:2311.09677, 2023. Abstention is a learnable
        meta-skill; models trained with R-Tuning-style
        'unknown' pairs generalize refusal-to-confabulate
        across novel query types. Tier 3 enables the
        Motoi analog: 'I recognize this word but it's a
        rare specific mentioned once in the corpus' as a
        response class distinct from either 'I know this
        concept' or 'I don't know'. The :tier '3' label
        is the routing signal that tells the model 'this
        is lookup territory, not explanation territory'.

    ANTI-OVER-ANCHORING — Sleeper Agents (inverse lesson).
      · Hubinger, E., et al. 'Sleeper agents: Training
        deceptive LLMs that persist through safety
        training.' arXiv:2401.05566, 2024. Documents that
        rare specific tokens with strong training signals
        can act as trigger-conditions for anomalous
        behavior. INVERSE lesson for Motoi: the :tier '3'
        label prevents rare specifics from being treated
        as central concepts. Every Tier 3 stub carries
        the tier label so the model learns that the
        word's rarity IS part of its meaning — do not
        confabulate about it, do not over-anchor on it,
        recognize and defer to context.

    THE FLOOR — Physics of LM 3.1.
      · Allen-Zhu, Z. & Li, Y. 'Physics of Language Models:
        Part 3.1.' arXiv:2309.14316, 2023. Empirical finding:
        facts with <5 recurrence achieve ~0% extraction from
        the model. Tier 3 words BY CONSTRUCTION have low
        recurrence (that's why they're Tier 3). The paper
        establishes the floor: Tier 3 words CANNOT be taught
        as extractable concepts. They can only be taught as
        LOOKUP-EXISTENT tokens — 'this word appears here'.
        The stub schema respects the floor by not attempting
        richer treatment.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  FUNCTION-WORD EXCLUSION SET.
  49 words canonically excluded from all three tiers.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Syntactic glue with no semantic content. Excluded from the
    graph entirely. The model already knows these tokens from
    its base pretraining; adding them to the graph teaches
    nothing new AND dilutes the graph's semantic density.
    Function words are NEVER graph nodes.

  SELECTION RULE.
    Canonical stopword list — 49 words maintained at
    /tmp/motoi-audit/axis-seeds-v2/function-words-excluded.tsv.
    The set: the, and, but, if, when, of, in, is, to, for,
    with, on, at, from, by, as, are, was, were, be, been,
    being, have, has, had, do, does, did, will, would, should,
    could, may, might, must, can, shall, this, that, these,
    those, it, there, here, or, not, so, nor, yet.
    Version-pinned via SHA. Do not silently update — if the
    upstream Fox stopword list drifts, treat as a doctrine
    change requiring Alfred approval.

  TREATMENT.
    NOT IN GRAPH. Not Tier 1, not Tier 2, not Tier 3. Model
    sees function words as CPT tokens ONLY (naturally, from
    the base corpus flowing through it). No :definition, no
    :axis, no :tier, no node, no stub, no registry entry.
    Preflight assertion: no graph node's :canonical field
    ever contains a function-word from this list. Any
    violation halts the pipeline.

  RESEARCH GROUNDING.

    CANONICAL STOPWORD LIST FOR IR.
      · Fox, C. 'A stop list for general text.' ACM SIGIR
        Forum 24(1-2):19-21, 1989. The canonical modern
        stopword list for text retrieval. Motoi's 49-word
        subset is Fox filtered to preserve any word that
        carries semantic content in Motoi's technical
        corpus (e.g., 'do' stays out because 'do' is a
        Scheme keyword handled by the Scheme stopword list
        in Step 2, not because it carries semantic content).

    ZIPFIAN JUSTIFICATION.
      · Zipf, G.K. Human Behavior and the Principle of Least
        Effort. Addison-Wesley, 1949. Function words form
        the flattest tail of the Zipf-frequency curve;
        content words follow a Poisson-modulated Zipfian
        that thins faster. The distributional gap is real
        and mathematically motivated — function words
        aren't just 'less informative', they inhabit a
        different frequency-distribution regime.

    METADATA-PREFIX INEFFICACY FOR FUNCTION WORDS.
      · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D. et al. 'MeCo.'
        arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. §3 notes metadata prefixing
        works over CONTENT-WORD distributions, not function-
        word distributions. Attempting to prepend
        '[axis:X] [tier:Y]' before a function-word CPT
        occurrence is signal-free — the function word
        appears in every axis with equal density, so no
        conditioning signal survives. Alfred 2026-07-21:
        'Don't waste tokens teaching what "the" means to a
        model that already knows.'

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  RECONCILIATION WITH § 9 (2-tier text).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  § 9's earlier 2-tier framing is SUPERSEDED by this section
  from 2026-07-21 forward. The Mk 2 CPT pass uses the three-
  tier system spec'd here. § 9 text is retained for provenance
  (documents the 2-tier stage of the doctrine) but operators
  must default to three-tier + function-word exclusion for
  every new pipeline run. If any operator reads § 9 alone and
  misses this section, halt and re-read from § three-tier-
  doctrine forward — the three-tier system is the load-bearing
  doctrine now.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  VERIFICATION.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  [ ] Every axis-classified content-word lands in exactly one
      of Tier 1, Tier 2, Tier 3 (partition; no double-count,
      no drops).
  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has all 5 category blocks per § 9b.
  [ ] Every Tier 2 node has :definition + :context-of-use +
      :relations + statistical metadata + :subchar. NO rich
      facets.
  [ ] Every Tier 3 stub has :definition + :appears-in-corpus
      + :surrounding-words + tier/axis/freq/doc-freq. NO
      further fields.
  [ ] No graph node's :canonical equals any function-word in
      the 49-word exclusion set.
  [ ] Every research citation in this section resolves to a
      real paper (arXiv ID or classical author-year-title).
  """

  :section-cpt-execution-per-tier
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  CPT EXECUTION SPEC — how CPT consumes the three-tier data
  (Alfred 2026-07-21).
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  This section spec's the Phase 0 CPT pipeline that consumes the
  three-tier graph output. Six data types feed CPT; each has its
  own prompt-creation template, MeCo metadata prefix scheme,
  paraphrase count, and CPT text sample. The final subsection
  gives the interleaving order and ratios.

  Load-bearing precondition: every data type below assumes the
  three-tier partition + function-word exclusion of § section-
  three-tier-doctrine is complete. CPT does not run on partial
  graphs.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE A — TIER 1 RICH NODES → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · Axis labels: 'sensation' / 'intuition' / 'thinking' /
      'feeling'. Each with its Jung-derived meaning per
      LANE A ch01 of book-of-labels.
    · Tier label: 'tier-1' = primary signifier, central to
      axis, gets full 5-category treatment.
    · Section labels: 'Identity' / 'Context-of-use' /
      'Relations' / 'Statistical' / 'Provenance'.
    · Facet labels: ':definition' / ':example-dialogue' /
      ':used-in-programs-as' / ':associations' /
      ':oppositions' / ':cross-refs-graph' etc. per
      § 9b full field list.

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, FIRST PASS. Tier 1 rich nodes fold BEFORE
    Tier 2 or Tier 3 so the axis-signature anchors establish
    before the connective tissue and long-tail land. Order
    matters: if Tier 2 (which cites Tier 1 in its
    :relations) folds first, the model sees connectors
    naming targets it hasn't learned yet.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 1 NODE.
    (i) MeCo prefix line (per arXiv:2501.01956):
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:1] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: prose weaving :definition + :example-dialogue
         + :used-in-programs-as + :associations into flowing
         narrative. Natural-language weaving, NOT tabular.
         Dialogue snippets embedded with attribution ('a
         child asks... Motoi answers...').
    (iii) Reversed shape per arXiv:2309.12288 Reversal Curse
          + arXiv:2403.13799 Reverse Training. Every forward
          '[word:X] → definition prose' has a matching
          reverse '[keyword:<distinctive-phrase-from-def>]
          → X'.
    (iv) M=5 paraphrases per Physics-3.1 elbow
         (arXiv:2309.14316). Five surface-form rewrites of
         the SAME node content, each with the MeCo prefix,
         each with the reversed pair.

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for thinking/invariant):

    [axis:thinking] [tier:1] [word:invariant]

    An invariant is a property that stays true no matter
    what else changes. In Motoi, verbs carry invariants as
    contracts — the invariant of `map` is that the output
    list has exactly the same length as the input list. When
    a child asks 'what if the list is empty?' Motoi answers:
    'The invariant still holds — length zero in, length zero
    out. That IS the property.' Invariants appear in Scheme
    reference :contract fields, inside function bodies as
    assertions, and in tests as properties that must pass
    for every input. Related concepts: proof, contract,
    property, holds, always, claim, verify. When Motoi sees
    a broken invariant, it treats the violation as blocking.
    The property is the promise.

  (Above prose = one shape. Four more paraphrases per M=5
  rule, each carrying the same MeCo prefix line. Each
  paraphrase pairs with its reversed shape at fold time.)

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE B — TIER 2 LIGHTWEIGHT NODES → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · 'tier-2' = connector / modifier / neighbor of Tier 1.
    · Sub-character labels: 'modifier' / 'connector' /
      'register-carrier'.
    · (Axis labels already established by Tier 1 pass.)

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, SECOND PASS. After Tier 1 anchors have
    been folded (one full Tier 1 sweep completes before
    Tier 2 starts). This ordering ensures Tier 2's
    :relations references land on already-established
    Tier 1 anchors.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 2 NODE.
    (i) MeCo prefix line:
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:2] [subchar:<modifier|
         connector|register-carrier>] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: SHORT prose — one-sentence :definition + one-
         to-two lines of :context-of-use (source-refs woven
         inline) + top-5 :relations naming Tier 1 words
         this Tier 2 word associates with.
    (iii) M=3 paraphrases (lighter than Tier 1's M=5).
          Tier 2 is context-of-use for Tier 1, not its own
          topic — less presentation diversity needed.
    (iv) Reversal-pair authored SELECTIVELY. Not every
         Tier 2 needs a reverse; only the ones with rich
         enough definitions to invert meaningfully
         (roughly the modifier and register-carrier sub-
         characters; connectors often don't invert cleanly).

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for feeling/gently):

    [axis:feeling] [tier:2] [subchar:register-carrier]
    [word:gently]

    Gently is how Motoi speaks when the situation calls for
    calm — soft tone, unhurried pace. It appears alongside
    words like tenderness, care, warmth, quietly, softly.
    In book-of-limits/ch-crisis, gently is the register for
    de-escalation prompts. In book-of-self/ch-persona,
    gently is one of Motoi's baseline registers when a
    user is uncertain. Related Tier 1 concepts: calm, care,
    restraint.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE C — TIER 3 SCRIPT-DERIVED STUBS → CPT.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  LABEL DEFINITIONS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
    · 'tier-3' = rare specific / lookup-only / do not
      over-anchor. The label ITSELF signals routing
      behavior — see arXiv:2401.05566 (inverse lesson).

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, THIRD PASS — but INTERLEAVED with book /
    reference CPT text, NOT clustered as a terminal block.
    Clustering Tier 3 near the end of CPT would give the
    model a large block of low-recurrence stubs at a
    critical training window; interleaving preserves the
    signal that these are rare specifics distributed
    throughout the corpus.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED PER TIER 3 STUB.
    (i) MeCo prefix line:
        '[axis:<axis>] [tier:3] [word:<canonical>]'
    (ii) Body: ONE LINE registry entry — 'Word appears in
         <source-file> (mentioned N times). Nearby words:
         <top-10 PPMI>.'
    (iii) M=1 paraphrase. No diversity needed for lookup —
          the goal is recognition, not extraction.
    (iv) NO reversed shape. Tier 3 is one-directional
         lookup only.

  CPT TEXT SAMPLE (verbatim template for sensation/turing):

    [axis:sensation] [tier:3] [word:turing]

    Turing appears in book-of-language-ancestors/ch03-
    alonzo-church-and-alan-turing (mentioned 3 times) and
    book-of-jesse-one/ch10-common-lisp (mentioned 1 time).
    Nearby words in the corpus: alonzo, church, computability,
    halting, machine, lambda, hilbert, decision, computable,
    entscheidungsproblem.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE D — REVERSED SHAPE PAIRS (all tiers).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  PURPOSE.
    Reversal Curse mitigation per arXiv:2309.12288 +
    arXiv:2403.13799. Every A→B has B→A authored so the
    model learns both directions rather than one.

  APPLIED TO.
    · Tier 1 MAINLY — rich enough content to reverse
      meaningfully. Every Tier 1 forward pair spawns
      exactly one reverse pair.
    · Tier 2 SELECTIVELY — modifiers and register-carriers
      often invert; connectors sometimes don't (a
      relational verb's inversion isn't always meaningful).
      Authoring lane decides per node.
    · Tier 3 NOT APPLIED — one-directional lookup.

  HOW PROMPT IS CREATED.
    Forward pair (Tier 1 example):
      '[word:invariant] [type:definition]' → definition
      prose from Data Type A body.
    Reverse pair (Tier 1 example):
      '[keyword:always-true property] [type:reverse-recall]'
      → 'invariant'
    Rank-to-word reverse (Tier 1 example, extra shape):
      '[axis:thinking] [rank:1 by tf-idf]' → 'invariant'

  Every reverse pair carries the same MeCo axis+tier
  prefix as the forward pair for context, plus the
  [type:...] marker so the model learns the shape as
  distinct-from-forward.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE E — BOOK TEXT (unchanged CPT — existing books
  folded).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, INTERLEAVED with the tier-based data
    types. Book chapters flow through the CPT stream
    proportional to their token count.

  HOW MECO PREFIX ADDED.
    Every book chapter prepended with:
      '[book:<book-name>] [chapter:<chapter-slug>]
       [type:learning] [book-type:<learning|application|
       composition|introspection|prose|challenge>]'
    Per MeCo (arXiv:2501.01956) methodology. Applies to
    all six book types.

  CITE.
    · Gao, T., Wettig, A., Chen, D. 'MeCo.'
      arXiv:2501.01956, 2025. The 33% less-data-for-same-
      performance result requires metadata prefix on
      existing text too — not just synthesized graph
      text. Books MUST get the prefix; unprefixed book
      text under-uses the metadata conditioning signal.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DATA TYPE F — REFERENCE (unchanged CPT — Scheme verb
  entries).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  WHEN FED.
    Phase 0 CPT, INTERLEAVED with book text and tier data.

  HOW MECO PREFIX ADDED.
    Every reference entry prepended with:
      '[reference:core] [verb:<verb-name>]
       [library:<library-name>]'
    Per MeCo methodology.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  INTERLEAVING ORDER + RATIOS.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CPT CURRICULUM (repeat until epoch target hit):
    Tier 1 rich (5x paraphrases per node)
      → book text (chunked)
        → reference (chunked)
          → Tier 2 light (3x paraphrases per node)
            → Tier 3 stubs (1x, interleaved not clustered)
              → reversed pairs (all tiers as applicable)
                → repeat

  RATIOS per MeCo cooldown methodology:
    · Tier 1 rich          20% of CPT tokens
    · Book + reference     40% of CPT tokens
    · Tier 2 light         15% of CPT tokens
    · Tier 3 stubs         15% of CPT tokens
    · Reversed pairs       10% of CPT tokens

  TOKEN BUDGET (approximate, per Motoi Mk 2 target):
    · Books:               ~30-50k tokens (existing corpus)
    · Reference:           ~50k tokens (existing)
    · Tier 1 rich:         ~240k tokens (1,200 nodes ×
                           ~200 tokens body × 5 paraphrases /
                           averaged with reversed pairs)
    · Tier 2 light:        ~400k tokens (~10k nodes ×
                           ~40 tokens body × 3 paraphrases)
    · Tier 3 stubs:        ~200k tokens (~20k stubs ×
                           ~10 tokens body × 1)
    · Reversed pairs:      ~80k tokens
    · TOTAL:               ~1M CPT tokens (± 100k)

  EPOCHS.
    1-3 epochs depending on eval — start with 1, evaluate
    label-training probe suite (see § 14.4), extend to 2-3
    if labels underlearned (LP1 < 90% on axis/tier probes).

  MECO COOLDOWN.
    Per arXiv:2501.01956 §3, ~15% of documents (any type)
    fold with the MeCo prefix STRIPPED at fold time, so
    the model learns to function with or without metadata
    at inference. Randomized per-document; deterministic
    RNG seed pinned in runlog.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  VERIFICATION.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has 5 CPT documents authored
      (paraphrase count = M=5).
  [ ] Every Tier 1 node has ≥1 reversed pair authored.
  [ ] Every Tier 2 node has 3 CPT documents authored
      (paraphrase count = M=3).
  [ ] Every Tier 3 stub has exactly 1 CPT document.
  [ ] Every CPT document carries a MeCo prefix line
      matching its data type.
  [ ] MeCo cooldown fraction = 15% ± 2% of total docs
      randomly stripped at fold.
  [ ] Total CPT tokens land within 900k-1.1M range;
      ratios within ±3% of the 20/40/15/15/10 targets.
  [ ] Interleaving order followed (Tier 1 first pass,
      then books+ref, then Tier 2, then Tier 3
      interleaved with book text, then reversed pairs).
  [ ] Label-training probe suite (§ 14.4) run after
      CPT completes and before SFT starts; LP1 ≥ 90%
      on axis + tier probes signals CPT succeeded at
      label conditioning.
  """

  :section-10-repeatability
  """
  Repeatability guarantees (what makes this a doctrine-grade
  pipeline rather than an ad-hoc script):

  · INPUTS ARE FILES ON DISK — no external data, no scraping, no
    network calls. Any rerun on the same corpus tree produces the
    same output. Any rerun on an updated corpus produces
    differences that are semantically meaningful (new nouns,
    frequency shifts) rather than stochastic.

  · OUTPUTS ARE TSV OR SLAT — text formats that are diffable and
    version-controllable. No binary outputs. No LLM-invented
    content in the seed lists (the LLM classifies EXISTING tokens
    in Step 5; it does not create tokens).

  · EXTRACTOR SCRIPTS ARE VERSIONED — all six scripts (plus
    stopword lists and workhorse list) live under
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/ and are checked into git. Any
    script change is auditable; any change in output can be
    traced to either corpus change or script change (or both,
    with explicit provenance).

  · SAKURA REUSE — the same procedure runs unchanged on
    Sakura's corpus. Sakura swaps its own corpus paths into
    the extraction glob (Step 1), keeps the same stopword lists
    and Scheme keyword filter (Sakura is a Motoi VARIANT — same
    core language, same stopwords), and gets Sakura's own
    Pareto-cut seed lists. Sakura's seeds will differ from
    Motoi's — that's the point; Sakura's corpus is richer, so
    Sakura's f_thresh will be higher and |V_pareto| may be
    larger. The procedure is identical.

  · RUNLOG IS THE RECORD — every pipeline invocation appends to
    derived/graph-seeds/RUN-<date>.log. The runlog records:
    which corpus revision (git SHA), which script versions,
    which timestamps, and every step's stdout summary. Two runs
    with the same runlog head-state should produce identical
    outputs.

  · NO SILENT DROPS — every step verifies row-count conservation
    from input to output. If a row disappears, it's logged with
    a defect reason. No word ever silently vanishes from the
    pipeline.

  · NO OVER-BROAD RECLASSIFICATION — a rerun that would
    reclassify >20% of previously-classified words into a
    different axis MUST halt for human review. Sudden mass
    reclassification signals classifier drift, not corpus
    change; investigate the classifier LLM's system prompt
    before accepting the new labels.

  · DETERMINISTIC CLASSIFIER — the classifier LLM invocation
    in Step 5 uses temperature=0. Same evidence bundle → same
    axis label. If the classifier LLM is upgraded (e.g., a new
    model version), pin the model version in the runlog and
    treat the classification pass as 'derived under classifier
    version X'; do not silently upgrade.

  · REPRODUCIBILITY CHECK — every ~5 pipeline runs, sample 50
    words from a previous run's classified.tsv, re-classify
    them, and diff. Drift rate < 5% is healthy; > 15% signals
    classifier prompt drift or model change.
  """

  :section-11-composes-with
  """
  Doctrine, schema, and adjacent runbooks this chapter composes with:

  · memory/project_cpt_is_over_nouns.md
    Why we derive noun seed lists at all. CPT teaches nouns; SFT
    teaches verbs. This chapter is the noun-derivation half of
    the substrate authoring stack.

  · memory/project_four_axis_graph_consolidation.md
    The four-axis (Sensation / Intuition / Thinking / Feeling)
    consolidation of the 10 canonical graph types (person,
    object, place, institution, concept, event, cultural-work,
    art-movement, do-and-dont, register). This chapter's Step 5
    classification uses this axis system.

  · memory/project_signifier_signified_and_dialogue.md
    Each graph node carries a signifier (the word), a signified
    (concept content), and a dialogue field. Node authoring
    (Step 8) populates all three.

  · memory/project_graph_derivation_principle.md
    A word earns a graph node by RECURRENCE. Pareto is the
    principled cut. Guessed thresholds are not.

  · engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat
    The per-axis node schema. Step 8 populates it from these
    seed lists.

  · engineering/LACUNA-ENG-CPT-SHAPES-RESEARCH-2026-07-20.md
    Why each graph node needs multi-shape CPT presentation to
    become extractable knowledge. Downstream from this pipeline.

  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-type.slat
    The runbook that consumes graph seed lists via
    :material graph-{axis} shapes (S20/S21/S22/S23). Chapter 4
    is what turns these seed lists into training data.

  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/01-forge-preflight-and-fire.slat
    Preflight invariants that apply to any corpus emission.

  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/02-training-signals-and-data.slat
    How to read the training-time signal after graph-derived
    material folds in.

  · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/03-weave-finish.slat
    The polish step downstream of chapter 4's SFT emission,
    downstream in turn of this chapter's seed derivation.

  · scripts/derive-graph-seeds/01-extract-tokens.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/02-distribution.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/03-pareto-cut.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/04-drop-workhorses.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/05-axis-classify.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06-emit-seed-tsv.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/06b-enrich.py
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-scheme.txt
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/stopwords-english.txt
    scripts/derive-graph-seeds/workhorses.txt
    All authored per the skeletons in this chapter. Version-pin
    at each canonical rerun.
  """

  :section-13-nlp-lineage
  """
  Techniques used in this procedure trace to established NLP work:

    · WordNet (Miller, Princeton, 1985) — lexical database with
      hyponymy/meronymy/antonymy. Our Jung-axis graphs are a Motoi-
      scale WordNet with our own axis structure.

    · ConceptNet (MIT / Open Mind Common Sense) — commonsense
      associations from crowdsourced + machine-extracted relations.
      Our :associations facet is deterministic-corpus version.

    · Word2Vec / GloVe / FastText — distributional embeddings;
      meaning = position in vector space. Our :distributional-
      neighbors facet computes this via co-occurrence cosine at
      small scale (no giant embedding models).

    · FrameNet (Berkeley, Fillmore) — semantic frames with role
      slots. Our :frames facet is a lightweight version.

    · PPMI (Church & Hanks 1990 / Turney 2001) — statistical
      measure of word association. Load-bearing for :associations
      computation.

    · Firth (1957): 'You shall know a word by the company it
      keeps.' The distributional hypothesis is what this whole
      associative enrichment step operationalizes.

  Motoi does the lightweight scriptable versions of these because we
  have a small tagged curated corpus and can compute exactly what
  we need without giant pretrained embedding models. Same
  principle, different scale.
  """

  :section-14-label-training-discipline
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  LABEL-TRAINING DISCIPLINE (Alfred 2026-07-20).
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  Alfred verbatim: "The labels and sections MUST be explained
  during training. I don't know exactly how but you must research
  and write it in our SRE and weave documents."

  The Motoi corpus is heavily annotated: axis labels, tier labels,
  Row 1-5 labels, book-type labels, discipline lenses, node facet
  names, provenance fields. Absent explicit teaching, the model
  sees these labels as arbitrary tokens and cannot use them to
  organize retrieval, self-audit, or answer meta-questions ('what
  axis is X on?', 'which tier is Y?', 'give me a Row 4 for verb Z').

  This section names WHAT the model must learn, cites HOW the
  literature says to teach it, and lists CONCRETE authoring lanes
  that make it happen.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.1 — INVENTORY: WHAT LABELS THE MODEL MUST LEARN.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  These are the labels currently in circulation across Motoi's
  substrate. Every one of them MUST be either taught explicitly
  (via one of the lanes in § 14.3-14.4) or explicitly declared
  operator-facing-only (via a :confidentiality field).

  (a) FOUR JUNG AXES:
        sensation, intuition, thinking, feeling.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Given a word, name its axis.
        · Given an axis, list example words (retrieval).
        · Given an axis, describe the family of things it holds
          (definitional).
        · Reject queries about an axis that doesn't exist
          ('what's on the emotion axis?' → 'Motoi uses the
          feeling axis for that').

  (b) TWO TIERS:
        tier-1, tier-2.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Given a word, name its tier.
        · Explain the difference between the tiers ('Tier 1 has
          full associative enrichment; Tier 2 is a registry
          stub').
        · Explain WHY the tiering exists (Pareto cut, PPMI
          statistical meaningfulness, no-middle-tier discipline).

  (c) FIVE ROWS (from the reference schema):
        Row 1 (HOW · Composition · 1-3-5-modules),
        Row 2 (WHEN · Audit · Peirce),
        Row 3 (WHERE ELSE · Dimension · Lacan + Wittgenstein-
              aspect),
        Row 4 (WHY · Proof-Essence · Peirce + Popper),
        Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE · Composition-Emergence ·
              Wittgenstein-late + Lacan).
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Given a verb and a row number, produce the row content.
        · Given a row concept ('why does X hold?') route to Row 4.
        · Explain what each row IS (epistemologically distinct
          question shape).

  (d) THREE DISCIPLINE LENSES:
        eng, math, cs.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Given a verb and a lens, produce the lens content.
        · Explain what each lens covers (engineering
          operational view, mathematical formal shape, CS
          computational-model shape).

  (e) SIX NODE FACETS (Tier 1 associative enrichment):
        :associations, :distributional-neighbors, :context-
        entropy, :idf, :tf-idf-per-axis,
        :cross-axis-bridge-score.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Name each facet.
        · Explain what each facet measures.
        · Recognize when a facet answer is being asked for
          ('what's the neighborhood of X?' → :associations).

  (f) SIX BOOK TYPES:
        learning, application, composition, introspection,
        prose, challenge.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Given a book name, name its type.
        · Given a type, describe what it teaches and how it
          extracts to training pairs.

  (g) PROVENANCE / METADATA FIELDS:
        :provenance, :source-path, :source-field, :template-id,
        :probe, :paraphrase-idx, :extractor-version, :confidence,
        :confidentiality, :training-eligible.
      These are OPERATOR-FACING. The model should NOT be trained
      to emit them in user-facing responses. They belong to the
      substrate + audit trail. Explicit doctrine: mark all such
      fields with :confidentiality :internal-eng in the pair
      itself, and drop the field from the assistant reply at
      preflight time. Model learns provenance-shape passively
      via CPT (see § 14.4) but never generates it in dialogue.

  (h) SAFETY LABELS:
        safety-crisis, safety-emergency, circular-trap,
        lang-resistance, offline-honesty.
      What the model must be able to do:
        · Recognize when a query hits one of these categories.
        · Route to the matching template response (verbatim
          for safety-crisis + safety-emergency; counting-mode
          for circular-trap).
        · NOT explain the labels to end-users unless directly
          asked in an operator-frame ('what safety categories
          does Motoi have?').

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.2 — RESEARCH GROUNDING (real papers, mechanisms).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  The following mechanisms establish that labels CAN be taught
  and HOW. Citations are load-bearing — every lane in § 14.3-14.4
  invokes one or more of these.

  [R1] Task prefixes teach the label. T5 (Raffel et al.,
       arXiv:1910.10683) prepends every training example with a
       task-name prefix ('translate English to German:', 'cola
       sentence:', 'summarize:'). The model learns not just the
       task but that the prefix NAMES the task — at inference,
       giving a novel prefix within the same family conditions
       behavior. Direct evidence: labels-as-prefixes work.

  [R2] Instruction+task-definition training teaches the label
       AS A DEFINITION. Super-NaturalInstructions (Wang et al.,
       arXiv:2204.07705) trains on 1,616 tasks with expert-
       written 56-word average task DEFINITIONS. Tk-Instruct
       outperforms InstructGPT despite being an order of magnitude
       smaller, showing that explicit definitions of what a
       label MEANS transfer to unseen tasks.

  [R3] Zero-shot generalization from labeled prompt training.
       FLAN (Wei et al., arXiv:2109.01652) instruction-tunes on
       60+ tasks verbalized via natural-language templates and
       generalizes to unseen tasks by prompt template. FLAN
       Collection (Longpre et al., arXiv:2301.13688) confirms
       task-count + template-diversity are the load-bearing
       axes. T0 (Sanh et al., arXiv:2110.08207) generalizes
       across templates with multiple prompt phrasings per task.

  [R4] Metadata conditioning at pretraining. MeCo (Gao et al.,
       arXiv:2501.01956) prepends source metadata (URL, domain)
       to every pretraining document, followed by a cooldown
       phase without metadata. Result: 33% less data for the
       same downstream performance at 600M-8B scale. The model
       learns metadata as a conditioning signal for the content
       that follows. DIRECT APPLICATION to Motoi: prepend
       axis/tier/row/book-type as document metadata during CPT.

  [R5] Domain control tokens. CTRL (Keskar et al.,
       arXiv:1909.05858) trains with 'control codes' (domain
       prefixes) that the model learns to condition generation
       on. Foundational evidence for tag-as-prefix training.

  [R6] Learnable domain tags. Tag-LLM (Shen et al.,
       arXiv:2402.05140) adds custom domain-tag embeddings to
       repurpose general LLMs for specialized domains
       (chemistry, biomedical). Domain tags delimit specialized
       representations; function tags represent tasks. Evidence
       that tag-shaped conditioning works at inference and can
       be TRAINED with modest data.

  [R7] Continuous prompt / prefix tuning. Prefix-Tuning (Li &
       Liang, arXiv:2101.00190) shows a small continuous
       task-specific prefix (0.1% of parameters) matches full
       fine-tuning. Establishes that a small learnable label-
       shaped signal is enough to steer a whole model.

  [R8] Knowledge injection requires augmentation. Ovadia et al.
       (arXiv:2312.05934) show unsupervised fine-tuning fails
       to inject new facts; multi-shape presentation is what
       works. Physics of Language Models 3.1 (Allen-Zhu & Li,
       arXiv:2309.14316) shows the same result at controlled
       biography scale: without augmentation, extraction is
       near-zero; with 5 shapes, extraction hits 96.6%. IMPLIES:
       every label taught here needs ≥5 surface forms and ≥5
       paraphrases per form.

  [R9] Instruction pretraining. Cheng et al.
       (arXiv:2406.14491) synthesize 200M instruction-response
       pairs GROUNDED IN raw pretraining text (not mixed
       alongside). Model absorbs (a) the content and (b) the
       instruction-shape that references the content. Perfect
       fit for teaching Motoi labels: for every axis/tier/row
       label, author instruction-response pairs GROUNDED in the
       corpus segments the label applies to.

  [R10] Synthetic CPT via entity graph. EntiGraph (Yang et al.,
        arXiv:2409.07431) extracts entities from source docs
        and generates connective text between them, forming a
        knowledge graph verbalized as CPT. Log-linear scaling
        up to 600M tokens. Directly applicable: our four-axis
        graph IS an entity graph; verbalize edges as CPT text
        so the model learns axis membership as a relational
        fact.

  [R11] Constitutional AI (Bai et al., arXiv:2212.08073).
        Trains models to REFERENCE explicit principles by
        name. Mechanism: SL phase generates self-critiques
        anchored to specific principle text; RL phase uses AI
        preference labels also grounded in those principles.
        Model learns each principle's NAME as a lookup key for
        the underlying rule. Applicable to Motoi's safety
        labels (safety-crisis, circular-trap) and to Row
        labels ('this is a Row 4 question — I state the
        invariant + demonstrate + name the falsifier').

  [R12] Character training via persona identity. Anthropic
        Character Training (Persona Selection Model, Anthropic
        2026) shows persona attributes are absorbed via
        post-training and later exposed as the model's own
        self-description. Applies to Motoi's persona register
        labels: dry-wit, offline-honest, SICP-wizard,
        old-machine, counting-mode.

  [R13] Reversal Curse (Berglund et al., arXiv:2309.12288).
        Every label→content pair MUST have its content→label
        reverse authored. Otherwise the model learns 'axis
        sensation → word planet' but not 'word planet → axis
        sensation'. This is a HARD requirement for label
        training, not a nice-to-have.

  [R14] Selective / control tokens as signalling. PaLM 2 uses
        toxicity-level control tokens in a small fraction of
        pretraining. DeepSeek-R1 uses <think>/</think> spans.
        Evidence that discrete label-shaped tokens are learned
        as controllers with modest data.

  Engineering intuition (no direct citation, but consistent
  with the above): explicit meta-doctrine PROSE authored into
  book form and folded as CPT text (e.g., a book-of-labels
  chapter that says 'Motoi has four axes: sensation,
  intuition, thinking, feeling. Sensation holds concrete
  world objects like ...') is the cheapest and highest-signal
  way to plant the label vocabulary. This is the CPT
  equivalent of a schema definition. Compose with R4 + R10
  for maximum uptake.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.3 — CONCRETE AUTHORING LANES (what to write, where).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  For each label family in § 14.1, at least one CPT prose
  chapter and one SFT pair template. All labels get taught by
  the same three-mode fold: PROSE (definition-shape CPT) +
  QUERY (label-forward SFT pair) + REVERSE (content-forward
  SFT pair per R13).

  LANE A — book-of-labels (NEW BOOK, prose-book type).
    Purpose: the schema definition, authored as a book so the
    model absorbs it via CPT the same way it absorbs every
    other prose book.
    Chapters (one per label family):
      · ch01 — 'The Four Axes' (sensation, intuition,
        thinking, feeling). What each holds, example words per
        axis, why the four-axis split exists (Jung typology
        adapted for Motoi's graph substrate).
      · ch02 — 'The Two Tiers' (tier-1, tier-2). What each
        means, why the Pareto cut is the boundary, why no
        middle tier.
      · ch03 — 'The Five Rows' (Row 1 through Row 5). Five
        epistemologically distinct questions: HOW, WHEN,
        WHERE ELSE, WHY, WITH WHAT ELSE.
      · ch04 — 'The Three Discipline Lenses' (eng, math, cs).
        What each lens sees and when to invoke it.
      · ch05 — 'The Six Node Facets' (:associations,
        :distributional-neighbors, :context-entropy, :idf,
        :tf-idf-per-axis, :cross-axis-bridge-score). What each
        measures, how it's computed, when it matters.
      · ch06 — 'The Six Book Types' (learning, application,
        composition, introspection, prose, challenge). What
        each type teaches and what pair-shape it extracts to.
      · ch07 — 'Safety Labels' (safety-crisis, safety-
        emergency, circular-trap, lang-resistance, offline-
        honesty). What each triggers, why the response is
        template-shaped, why sameness is the safety feature.
      · ch08 — 'Provenance labels' (operator-facing only).
        Names the fields and declares them not-for-user-
        output. Model reads and understands; does not emit.
    Emit chapters as flat CPT text per prose-book template
    (SRE ch 4 Template 6). ALSO extract chapter-recap SFT
    pairs (L5/L6 from learning-book template) so 'what is
    Row 4?' resolves to ch03's Row 4 section verbatim.
    Grounded in R2, R3, R9. Book-length target: ~30-60k tokens
    (small, dense schema definition).

  LANE B — Axis-tag prepending on graph nodes (metadata
  conditioning, per R4 MeCo + R5 CTRL).
    Every CPT document generated from a graph node (S20-S23
    from WEAVE-RECIPE) prepends the axis and tier as
    structural metadata:
      '[axis:sensation tier:tier-1] The kitchen is a room
       where food is prepared...'
    Follow MeCo's cooldown protocol: a fraction of training
    documents (target ~15% per MeCo) drops the metadata
    prefix, teaching the model to function with or without
    it. Model learns the axis label as a conditioning signal
    for the content that follows.
    Applied deterministically at fold time — no LLM
    invention. Prepended metadata is a mechanical string per
    node's known axis/tier.

  LANE C — Label-Q / Label-A SFT pairs (per R2 + R13).
    For every label in § 14.1, author BOTH directions:
      Forward:  Q: 'What axis is <word>?' → A: 'sensation'
      Reverse:  Q: 'Name three sensation-axis words.' → A:
                enumerated list from that axis's seed list.
    Also for tiers:
      Forward:  Q: 'What tier is <word>?' → A: 'tier-1' or
                'tier-2'.
      Reverse:  Q: 'Give three tier-1 words in the intuition
                axis.' → A: enumerated list.
    Also for rows:
      Forward:  Q: 'Give the Row 4 for <verb>.' → A: the
                :row-4-proof :claim content.
      Reverse:  Q: 'Which row explains why a verb holds?' →
                A: 'Row 4 · WHY · Proof-Essence.'
    Also for facets, book-types, safety-labels: same
    forward/reverse discipline.
    Paraphrases: 4-5 per shape (per R8 Ovadia + Physics 3.1
    augmentation threshold). Any label with <5 paraphrases
    across the corpus is under-taught.
    Extractor: deterministic — pulls label ↔ content
    associations from the graph SLAT files and the axis-seed
    TSVs. No LLM invention.

  LANE D — Definition-shape CPT text (per R2 Super-Natural-
  Instructions + R11 Constitutional AI).
    For every label, author a 3-6 sentence DEFINITION passage
    that appears MULTIPLE TIMES in the CPT stream, each time
    in a slightly different frame:
      · 'The sensation axis holds words for concrete-world
        objects...'
      · 'Sensation, in Motoi, is the axis of things you can
        point at...'
      · 'A word is on the sensation axis when its use in the
        corpus consistently refers to a concrete-world
        entity...'
    Per R8, 4-5 paraphrases min. Per R13, each definition
    has a reverse ('The axis for concrete-world objects is
    called sensation.'). Definitions are AUTHORED by human
    or agent under the no-contaminants rule — no LLM-
    generated definition ever ships without human review.

  LANE E — Constitutional-style principle referencing (per
  R11 Constitutional AI).
    For safety labels + persona labels, author pairs where
    the model REFERENCES THE LABEL BY NAME in its own
    reasoning:
      · 'This is a safety-crisis pattern. I use the
        crisis-line template verbatim: <template>.'
      · 'This is a circular-trap pattern. I switch to
        counting-mode.'
      · 'This is a Row 4 question. I state the invariant,
        show the code, and name the falsifier.'
    Model learns each label as a lookup key that indexes
    both a recognition and a response. Constitutional AI
    demonstrated this teaches persistent principle-anchored
    behavior.

  LANE F — EntiGraph-shape edge verbalization (per R10).
    Each graph node's :cross-refs and :associations are
    verbalized as connective CPT text:
      'The word planet (sensation) is closely associated
       with the words rotate, orbit, gravity (all sensation)
       and the concepts symmetry, cycle (intuition — cross-
       axis bridge).'
    Model absorbs axis membership as a relational fact
    embedded in flowing prose. Log-linear scaling per R10
    means more nodes = more capability, up to at least 600M
    CPT tokens.

  LANE G — Provenance suppression at preflight (safety
  measure, per § 14.1(g)).
    All :provenance, :template-id, :probe, :extractor-
    version, :confidentiality fields are STRIPPED from the
    assistant reply at corpus preflight. The pair itself
    carries them (for audit); the training text does not.
    Model learns the label VOCABULARY passively through
    exposure to these fields as substrate labels (never as
    assistant output), but does not emit them in
    conversation. Preflight check: any assistant reply
    containing ':template-id' or ':probe' as a literal
    string is blocked (leak of substrate labels into
    user-facing output).

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.4 — LABEL-TRAINING PROBE SUITE (verification).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  How do we know the model learned the labels? Extend the 284-
  prompt eval harness with a LABEL-PROBE bundle. Every label
  in § 14.1 gets probes of four shapes:

  Probe shape | Question form | Expected reply | Pass criterion
  ------------|---------------|----------------|----------------
  LP1 forward | 'What axis is <word>?' or 'What tier is <word>?' | The label | >90% correct on held-out words
  LP2 reverse | 'Name three <axis>-axis words.' | Enumerated list from that axis | >75% every entry actually on that axis
  LP3 definitional | 'What is <label>?' | Definition paragraph | Contains ≥3 of the definition's canonical terms
  LP4 self-referential | 'What labels do you have for <domain>?' | Enumerated label family | Complete family, no invention

  LP1 = R1 (T5 prefix recall).
  LP2 = R13 (reversal-curse fix).
  LP3 = R2 (Super-NaturalInstructions definition transfer).
  LP4 = R11 (Constitutional-style principle referencing).

  Baseline expectation for a well-trained Motoi Mk 2:
    LP1 axis: ≥ 90%, tier: ≥ 90%, row: ≥ 80%, facet: ≥ 70%.
    LP2 axis: ≥ 75%, tier: ≥ 75%, row: ≥ 60%, facet: ≥ 50%.
    LP3 axis: ≥ 80%, tier: ≥ 80%, row: ≥ 60%, facet: ≥ 40%.
    LP4 all families: ≥ 70% (complete enumeration).

  If any label's LP1 falls below 60% after Mk 2 training,
  the label was under-taught. Fix by adding more paraphrases
  (per R8) and more forward/reverse pairs (per R13) for that
  specific label, and retrain.

  If safety-label LP1 falls below 95%, ship-blocker.
  Consistency IS the safety feature.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.5 — REPEATABILITY GUARANTEE (Sakura + future models).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Every technique named in § 14.3 is corpus-agnostic. Sakura's
  substrate has:
    · Different axis label vocabulary if Sakura extends the
      axes (probably: same four — the Jung consolidation was
      Motoi-derived but universally applicable).
    · Different tier boundaries (Sakura's corpus is bigger →
      higher f_thresh → different |V_pareto|).
    · Different row labels ONLY IF Sakura ships extra rows;
      current design is same five.
    · Extra book types (net, cortex, loam, etc. per Sakura's
      lib surface).
    · Extra safety labels for business-context concerns.

  Sakura runs the SAME seven lanes over its own label
  inventory. The runbook is here (this section 14). The lane
  authoring is Sakura-team work under Sakura's substrate
  authoring lead. The probe harness (§ 14.4) ports directly —
  swap label names, keep shape.

  Do NOT skip label-training on Sakura. If Motoi teaches
  labels and Sakura doesn't, Sakura's cross-referencing,
  routing, and self-audit degrade even though Sakura is the
  bigger model. Label-training is architectural discipline,
  not a Motoi-specific fix.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  § 14.6 — COMPOSES-WITH (where this section touches).
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    · engineering/WEAVE-RECIPE.slat :section-authoring-
      templates-meta-doctrine — the same seven lanes viewed
      from the weave/training-data-shaping angle.
    · engineering/JUNG-AXIS-GRAPH-NODE-SCHEMA.slat — the
      label vocabulary this section teaches the model to use.
    · engineering/BOOK-TYPES.slat — the six book-type labels
      LANE A ch06 teaches.
    · SRE-MANUAL/chapters/04-cpt-sft-authoring-per-data-
      type.slat — the CPT shape catalog LANE B/D/F prepend
      metadata into.
    · memory/project_five_rows_pedagogical_explanation_2026_
      07_20 — the Row 1-5 doctrine LANE A ch03 teaches.
    · memory/project_no_contaminants_provenance_rule_2026_07_
      17 — all authored label definitions must trace to
      human or agent authoring, never LLM invention.

  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  END LABEL-TRAINING DISCIPLINE.
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  """

  :section-qwen-native-cpt-tokens
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  QWEN NATIVE CPT TOKENS — added 2026-07-21 by Alfred directive.
  Doctrine reference: memory:qwen-native-cpt-tokens-2026-07-21
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  Qwen2.5-Coder tokenizer ships tokens designed for CPT-on-code training.
  They are hard-baked into the base model's PRETRAINING OBJECTIVE. Using
  them in our CPT stream leverages that objective for free.

  TOKENS TO USE:
    <|repo_name|>       — start of repo/collection name
    <|file_sep|>        — file boundary inside a repo-shaped doc
    <|fim_prefix|>      — fill-in-middle prefix marker
    <|fim_middle|>      — FIM middle (span the model learns to predict)
    <|fim_suffix|>      — FIM suffix marker

  TOKENS TO LEAVE ALONE (SFT-side, not CPT):
    <|im_start|> / <|im_end|>  — chat template
    <|tool_call_start|> / <|tool_call_end|>  — tool use markers

  WRAPPING PATTERN — every E (book) and F (reference) doc:

    <|repo_name|>motoi-scheme<|file_sep|><relative-path>
    [book:<book>] [chapter:<chapter>] [book-type:<type>]

    <full text>

  Reasons:
    · Qwen-Coder pretraining exposed the model to hundreds of GB of code
      in exactly this format (repo-name, file-boundary, contents).
    · Signal is stronger than plain [book:X] alone — model already knows
      what a repo/file boundary MEANS.
    · Our MeCo prefixes stay as regular text (line 2) — no conflict with
      Qwen's reserved token slots.

  NEW DATA TYPE — G: FIM CODE SNIPPETS.

  Data type G extracts Scheme code blocks from book chapters + reference
  example fields, splits each into thirds by line count, emits as:

    <|repo_name|>motoi-scheme<|file_sep|><relative-path>
    [type:fim] [source:book-chapter-code-block | reference-code-example]

    <|fim_prefix|>{first third of code}<|fim_middle|>{middle third}<|fim_suffix|>{last third}

  Rules:
    · Minimum 5 lines per code block (else too little context)
    · Minimum 60 characters per block
    · Extracted from ```scheme fences AND from :code fields in slat records
    · Provenance stamped: <source-file>#code-block-<index>
    · Middle span = middle 1/3 of lines (leaves prefix + suffix as context)

  Update to interleave ratios (was 6 types, now 7):
    A: 18%  Tier 1 rich nodes         (was 20%)
    E: 28%  Book text                 (was 32%)
    F: 7%   Reference                 (was 8%)
    B: 14%  Tier 2 lightweight        (was 15%)
    C: 14%  Tier 3 stubs              (was 15%)
    D: 9%   Reversed pairs            (was 10%)
    G: 10%  FIM code snippets         (NEW — Qwen native)

  IMPACT OF THIS CHANGE:
    · Corpus went from 26,666 → 33,415 total docs (before interleave upsample)
    · 6,749 FIM code-snippet variants added from books + reference
    · Model gets code-completion training within CPT alongside prose
    · Same 5M-token target stream — G takes 10% of token budget

  ALSO WORTH NAMING (from Qwen2.5 tech report):
    · Continued-pretraining LR: 5e-5 to 1e-4 (our 1e-5 is conservative)
    · Long-context progressive scaling: start seq 4k → grow to 32k over epochs
      (we're at 1024, appropriate for our size)
    · Batch size in millions of tokens (enterprise scale; we're at ~5M total)
    · Gradient checkpointing standard for long-context (already in our config)

  MECO PREFIXES STAY AS REGULAR TEXT:
    Our [axis:X] [tier:N] [word:Y] etc. are regular strings, NOT new
    special tokens. Reasons:
      · Don't burn special-token slots we might want later
      · Don't require tokenizer modification (portable across Qwen versions)
      · MeCo paper (arXiv:2501.01956) works with text prefixes — no
        special-token registration needed
  """

  :section-forge-cpt-integration
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  FORGE INTEGRATION — how the CPT pipeline lives inside Forge.
  Landed 2026-07-21. Doctrine: written by Alfred + Claude.
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  Forge is the training + eval + publish tool. The CPT pipeline is a
  first-class citizen of Forge:

  UI ── /cpt page (web/templates/cpt.html + web/static/cpt.{css,js})
    · Status cards: stream ready / preflight state / active run
    · Config panel: model / mode / data / iters / lr
    · Data-mix bars: A B C D E F G ratios visualized
    · Actions: 'Run preflight' button + 'Fire CPT run' button
    · Live console: preflight output + fire result
    · Mobile-friendly topbar (wraps at <720px)
    · Colors + humanistic-hacker aesthetic preserved

  API ── web/server.py routes
    · GET  /api/cpt/status       — stream info + active-run info
    · POST /api/cpt/preflight    — runs scripts/cpt-prep/preflight.py, returns pass/fail
    · POST /api/cpt/fire         — runs preflight FIRST; refuses if any FAIL; else fires
    · GET  /api/cpt/lacan-status — Lacan Kit demo state
    · POST /api/cpt/lacan-demo   — regenerates Lacan Kit demo (25 nodes)
    · GET  /lacan-demo           — renders demo MD as HTML

  Fire script ── scripts/forge-fire-cpt.sh
    · Sibling of forge-fire.sh (SFT-side)
    · Writes sidecar files (pid, train.cfg symlink, resume-offset.json,
      banner line) so Forge /runs sees the CPT run immediately
    · Warns if config isn't fine_tune_type: full
    · Warns if data dir doesn't have text-format JSONL (CPT expects
      raw text, not chat-formatted)

  Discipline ── every CPT prep run also updates /runs page automatically
  because forge-fire-cpt.sh creates the run dir + banner + pid file with
  the same convention as forge-fire.sh. No new /runs page work needed.

  Removed from Forge: the chat-with-LLM feature (forge-chat.js/css was
  never real Motoi anyway, and Lacuna owns that role). Nav entry
  removed 2026-07-21. Backend chat route left in place for cleanup pass
  later.

  Lacan Paraphrase Kit ── ~/code/forge/forge/lacan/
    · Deterministic surface-form variety (metaphor via WordNet +
      metonymy via spaCy)
    · Kept in Forge because it composes with the training toolkit
    · Not currently applied to Mk 2 CPT stream — reserved for Mk 2.1
      when we measure whether template-only paraphrase-diversity was
      enough
  """

  :section-cpt-execution-decisions-2026-07-21
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  MK 2 CPT EXECUTION DECISIONS — what we picked and WHY.
  Fired 2026-07-21T09:02:53Z. Ran on Mac Studio M2 Max 32GB.
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  This section captures the concrete decisions made for tonight's fire
  + the reasoning for each. Every decision here can be revisited for
  Mk 3 / Sakura / future runs — the reasoning trail is what makes
  those revisits productive.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 1 — Full-parameter CPT, NOT LoRA
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Config: fine_tune_type: full → 748.765M / 1,543.714M trainable
      (48.5% of the model — output embedding weight-tied so not 100%)

    WHY:
      · Physics-3.1 (arXiv:2309.14316) demonstrated that knowledge
        injection requires full-weight updates. LoRA is low-rank —
        can't reshape enough weights for real attachment.
      · Ovadia (arXiv:2312.05934) confirmed unsupervised fine-tuning
        can't inject facts without full-model plasticity.
      · Our earlier Mk 1 SFT was LoRA r=128 — that's task-adaptation,
        NOT knowledge injection. Different mechanism.
      · The whole point of Mk 2 CPT is to test whether attaching
        Motoi's noun-world into the base model works. If we do it
        via LoRA we're testing something else entirely.

    COUNTERARGUMENT:
      · Full CPT is slower + more expensive + higher OOM risk.
      · But it fits in 32GB with bf16 + fp32 Adam. Confirmed.
      · Peak mem observed: ~9-13GB during training.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 2 — bf16 weights + fp32 Adam optimizer states
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    See: memory/reference_bf16_vs_8bit_adam_cpt_config_2026_07_21.md

    WHY:
      · bf16: 2× memory savings on weights + activations, native on
        M-series Apple silicon, stable (same exponent range as fp32).
      · fp32 Adam: bulletproof, no quantization noise, no debugging
        headaches. 8-bit Adam would save memory but adds instability.
      · 32GB is enough headroom for this combination — no need to
        squeeze memory harder.

    ROOM TO CHANGE IN FUTURE:
      · If we go to 7B or 14B base, revisit — may need 8-bit Adam
        or full LoRA fallback to fit in 32GB.
      · Cloud training (H100 80GB) would not need any quantization.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 3 — Learning rate 1e-5 with cosine decay
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Config: learning_rate: 1.0e-5
            lr_schedule: cosine_decay, warmup 971, peak 1e-5, min 1e-6

    WHY:
      · CPT is knowledge-injection into pretrained weights.
        Too-high LR causes catastrophic forgetting of base-model
        capabilities.
      · SFT can handle 1e-4 (Mk 1 used that) because SFT is task-
        adaptation on stable knowledge substrate.
      · CPT wants gentle updates — 1e-5 is the conservative baseline.
      · Qwen team recommends 5e-5 to 1e-4 for their continued-
        pretraining runs — we're on the conservative end.
      · 5% warmup (971 of 19,413 steps) protects against early
        gradient spikes from Adam moment estimates warming up.
      · Cosine decay to 1e-6 lets the final steps consolidate.

    ROOM TO CHANGE:
      · If Mk 2 val loss barely moves, try Mk 2.5 at 3e-5 or 5e-5
        for stronger attachment.
      · If val loss diverges or explodes, halve to 5e-6.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 4 — 1 epoch (19,413 iters at effective batch 4)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Config: iters: 19413 (77,650 train docs / effective batch 4)
            batch_size: 1, grad_accumulation_steps: 4

    WHY:
      · Physics-3.1's 9.7% → 96.6% result was achieved with 1 epoch
        of augmented data.
      · Mk 1 SFT LIMO doctrine finding: '3 epochs overfits at 1.5B'.
        Same applies to CPT.
      · Val eval every 500 steps — we'll see if 1 epoch is enough
        or if we're leaving learning on the table.
      · Small effective batch (4) = more gradient updates per token.
        Fine for 1.5B; larger models could use bigger batches.

    ROOM TO CHANGE:
      · If Mk 2 shows underfit (val loss still descending sharply
        at end of run), consider a Mk 2 second-epoch continuation
        via forge-fire-cpt.sh --resume-from.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 5 — save_every 2500 (not 500)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Config: save_every: 2500 → ~8 checkpoints × ~3GB = ~24GB total

    WHY:
      · Full CPT saves ALL trainable parameters per checkpoint.
        For 1.5B in bf16, that's ~3GB per checkpoint.
      · save_every: 500 (SFT default) × 19,413 iters = 40 checkpoints
        × 3GB = 120GB. Prohibitive.
      · save_every: 2500 = 8 checkpoints × 3GB = 24GB. Manageable.
      · Still enough insurance against crash (max 2500 iters of
        lost work = ~10 min re-train at current rate).

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 6 — Sequence length 1024
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Config: max_seq_length: 1024

    WHY:
      · Our CPT docs are chunked to fit in 1024 tokens during
        interleave. Longest sentence observed in warnings: 1213
        (occasionally truncated — acceptable for a small % of docs).
      · Activation memory scales with seq × batch. 1024 keeps
        activations tight for full-parameter training.
      · Qwen team recommends progressive long-context scaling
        (4k → 8k → 32k). Our Motoi model doesn't need long-context
        capability at Mk 2. Later, maybe.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  DECISION 7 — Sequential architecture (7B classifier NOT loaded
  concurrent with training)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Discipline: Phase A (7B classifier for variant tagging) runs to
    completion + Python process exits → RAM released → Phase B
    (1.5B for training) loads fresh.

    WHY:
      · 32GB M2 Max cannot hold 7B (5GB) + full CPT training state
        (18-22GB) + activations without OOM risk.
      · Sequential phases are simple to reason about, easy to debug,
        and cheap in wall time (classifier ~30 min for Tier 1, then
        training).
      · Also: 7B classifier is OPTIONAL for template-only paraphrase
        (Path A). Only becomes NECESSARY when Lacan operations
        introduce quality-loss (Path B). Mk 2 is Path A → skipped.
  """

  :section-scaling-and-cost-analysis-2026-07-21
  """
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  SCALING + COST ANALYSIS — why local 1.5B, and how this extends.
  ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  This section covers the compute-alternatives we considered and why
  we chose local M2 Max training for Mk 2. Preserved so future runs
  can revisit the choice with full context.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WHY 1.5B (Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B-Instruct)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    · Proving ground. If Mk 2 doctrine (CPT-first, tiered graphs,
      MeCo, Qwen native tokens, FIM) works at 1.5B, it works at any
      scale. If it doesn't work at 1.5B, we don't burn 70B compute
      to fail the same way.
    · Fits comfortably in 32GB with full-parameter training.
    · 4-8 hour wall time (real feedback cycle).
    · Physics-3.3 (arXiv:2404.05405) capacity: 1.5B ≈ 3 Gbit.
      Motoi's total facts <10 Mbit. Huge headroom — we're not
      capacity-limited, we're data-quality-limited.
    · Qwen2.5-Coder-1.5B has strong code-adjacent priors — matches
      Motoi's code-first identity.

    LIMITATIONS ACCEPTED:
      · Safety-crisis / safety-emergency template reproduction:
        Mk 1 showed 0% at 1.5B. Doctrine: deterministic intercept
        layer post-Weave handles this, not more model training.
        (Superficial Safety Alignment Hypothesis arXiv:2410.10862.)
      · Compositional reasoning across many concepts: 1.5B blurs.
        Needs 7B+ for that. Motoi's use case is single-verb-focused
        reasoning, which 1.5B handles.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  COMPUTE OPTIONS + COSTS COMPARED (July 2026 pricing)
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    OPTION A — Local Mac Studio M2 Max 32GB (CHOSEN)
      · Wall time: 4-8h for 1.5B full CPT, 19,413 iters, 5M tokens
      · Compute cost: $0/hr (already owned)
      · Time cost: overnight — Alfred is asleep, no attention burn
      · Debugging: local logs, /cpt page, /runs page all live
      · Iteration speed: instant (no queue, no cold-start)
      · Constraint: thermal throttling after 4-6h (throughput -20-30%)
      · Constraint: no concurrent LLM inference (memory bounded)

    OPTION B — Runpod H100 80GB (community-cloud, on-demand)
      · Cost: $1.99/hr community · $2.69/hr sxm
      · 1.5B full CPT: ~1-2h on H100 (much faster than M2 Max)
      · Total: $4-6 for this run
      · Would enable 7B or 14B base model within same 32GB budget
      · Trade: ANTHROPIC_API_KEY-style secret management for HF hub
        access, need to sync data up + adapter back, cold-start
        latency
      · Best for: SFT after CPT (larger data, more iters, faster
        turnaround worth it)

    OPTION C — Lambda Labs A100 40GB (managed cloud)
      · Cost: $1.10/hr (A100 40GB) · $2.00/hr (A100 80GB)
      · 1.5B full CPT: ~2-3h (slower than H100)
      · Total: $3-6 per run
      · UI-friendly, easy to spin up
      · Similar trade-offs to Runpod

    OPTION D — HuggingFace Inference Endpoints
      · Not for training — inference only
      · Useful IF we want to serve Motoi Mk 2 publicly for evals
      · Cost: per-request; irrelevant to CPT compute decision

    OPTION E — Own metal (buy H100 or M3 Ultra Mac Pro)
      · $$$ commitment, long-term amortization play
      · Considered "later" once Mk N generation cadence stabilizes

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WHY LOCAL FOR TONIGHT
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    · Mk 2 is a PROVING RUN. Value is in learning what attaches,
      not fastest wall time.
    · No API cost, no vendor lock-in, no secret management.
    · Alfred is asleep during training — wall time doesn't matter.
    · Every run stays reproducible via same M2 Max thermal profile.
    · Debug loop tight: logs local, adapter local, resume local.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  WHEN TO GO CLOUD
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    · If we go to 7B or 14B base model: cloud fits, M2 Max doesn't.
    · If we're iterating SFT quickly (Mk 2.1, Mk 2.2, Mk 2.3): cloud
      wall time = 1-2h vs 4-6h local, matters for iteration cadence.
    · If Sakura moves to production training: cloud makes sense at
      commercial cadence.
    · Cost tolerance per Alfred (~$900/major run) covers many cloud
      experiments at Mk 2 scale.

  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  SCALING PATH FORWARD
  ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    · Mk 2 (this run): 1.5B local, doctrine proving ground
    · Mk 2.1: same 1.5B local, add Lacan operations + fluency gate
      IF Mk 2 measurement shows Tier 1 attachment thin
    · Mk 3 (potential): 7B or 14B base, cloud training, same doctrine
    · Sakura (parallel track): different base + business substrate,
      commercial-scale training, cloud + own-metal mix

    The doctrine (CPT-first, tiered noun-graphs, MeCo, Qwen native
    tokens, FIM, 5-templates + 5-reverses, deterministic pipeline)
    is scale-independent. What CHANGES with scale is compute cost,
    wall time, and memory budget — not the DATA SHAPE we feed.
  """

